{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8664e1b60bb4a6a1", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t\n2\t\n3\tCyclic-Prefix-Free OFDM With Tail-Reuse Reconstruction for Distributed Acoustic Sensing\n4\t\n5\t \n6\t \n7\t Report GitHub Issue\n8\t ×\n9\t \n10\t\n11\t \n12\t\n13\t Title:\n14\t \n15\t\n16\t \n17\tContent selection saved. Describe the issue below:\n18\t\n19\t Description:\n20\t \n21\t \n22\t\n23\t \n24\t Submit without GitHub\n25\t Submit in GitHub\n26\t \n27\t \n28\t\n29\t \n30\t arXiv is now an independent nonprofit!\n31\t Learn more\n32\t ×\n33\t \n34\t\n35\t \n36\t\n37\t \n38\t Back to arXiv\n39\t \n40\t \n41\t\n42\t \n43\t \n44\t Why HTML?\n45\t \n46\t \n47\t \n48\t \n49\t Report Issue\n50\t \n51\t \n52\t \n53\t \n54\t \n55\t \n56\t Back to Abstract\n57\t \n58\t \n59\t \n60\t \n61\t \n62\t \n63\t Download PDF\n64\t \n65\t \n66\t \n67\t \n68\t \n69\t \n70\t \n71\t \n72\t \n73\t \n74\t \n75\t \n76\t \n77\t \n78\t \n79\t \n80\t \n81\t \n82\t \n83\t \n84\t \n85\t \n86\t \n87\t \n88\t \n89\t \n90\t \n91\t \n92\t \n93\t \n94\t \n95\t \n96\t \n97\t \n98\t \n99\t\n100\tAbstract\n101\t\n102\tI Introduction\n103\t\n104\tII Principle and Signal Model\n105\t\n106\tII-A Finite-Memory DAS Channel and Effective Range Response\n107\t\n108\tII-B Repeated No-CP OFDM Tail-Reuse Reconstruction\n109\t\n110\tII-C Design Consequences: Overhead, Vibration Bandwidth, and Range\n111\t\n112\tII-D Validity Boundary and Practical Interpretation\n113\t\n114\tIII Numerical Simulation\n115\t\n116\tIII-A Simulation Configuration\n117\t\n118\tIII-B Tail-Reuse and Range-Condition Verification\n119\t\n120\tIII-C Dynamic Sensing and Slow-Time Bandwidth\n121\t\n122\tIII-D Bandwidth Scaling at a Fixed Reporting Interval\n123\t\n124\tIV Experimental Setup and Verification\n125\t\n126\tIV-A Experimental Setup\n127\t\n128\tIV-B Experimental Verification\n129\t\n130\tV Conclusion\n131\t\n132\tReferences\n133\t\n134\t \n135\t License: arXiv.org perpetual non-exclusive license\n136\t \n137\t \n138\t\n139\tarXiv:2607.18687v1 [eess.SP] 21 Jul 2026\n140\t\n141\tCyclic-Prefix-Free OFDM With Tail-Reuse Reconstruction for Distributed Acoustic Sensing\n142\t\n143\tZiang Chen, Zhiyang Xue, Zhongxing Tian, Zeyu Feng, Dongdong Zou,\n144\t\n145\tYi Cai*, Fellow, Optica and Huan Huang*, Member, IEEE\n146\tManuscript received Month Day, Year; revised Month Day, Year. (Corresponding authors:\n147\tYi Cai; Huan Huang.)The authors are with Soochow University, Suzhou, China (e-mail:\n148\tyicai@suda.edu.cn; huanghuan@suda.edu.cn).\n149\t\n150\tAbstract\n151\t\n152\tOrthogonal frequency-division multiplexing (OFDM) enables frequency-domain reconstruction of the\n153\tdistributed Rayleigh backscatter channel in coherent distributed acoustic sensing (DAS). However,\n154\tan explicitly transmitted cyclic prefix (CP) lengthens the probing period and lowers the slow-time\n155\tNyquist limit of each range cell. Here, we investigate a repeated cyclic-prefix-free OFDM (No-CP\n156\tOFDM) waveform for DAS, using the preceding useful-period tail as a virtual cyclic extension. We\n157\tderive the finite-memory range condition for tail-reuse reconstruction and identify circular folding\n158\twhen the useful period is shorter than the physical channel memory. Analysis shows that, for a fixed useful-block length\n159\tand fiber memory, removing the explicit CP raises the period-limited highest unaliased vibration\n160\tfrequency without altering the occupied-bandwidth-limited spatial resolution. For a 5.2-km numerical configuration, a 75-MSa/s\n161\tprocessing rate and a 4096-sample useful block yield a 54.61-μ\\mus No-CP period and a 9.16-kHz\n162\tslow-time Nyquist limit. Simulations verify tail reuse and the predicted range-folding boundary, and demonstrate recovery\n163\tof 100 vibration events spanning 800 Hz to 8800 Hz. A bandwidth-scaling simulation further shows\n164\tthat jointly processing fine spatial observations improves differential-phase reliability and\n165\treconstruction SNR at a fixed reporting interval under the modeled conditions. Experiments on a 5.2-km coherent DAS link with\n166\t111.984-MHz occupied OFDM\n167\tbandwidth blindly localize 500-Hz and 3-kHz piezoelectric transducer (PZT) vibrations at 5063.7 m\n168\tand 5070.1 m, respectively. The corresponding waveforms and spectra are recovered from the detected\n169\trange bins. These experiments establish the feasibility of tail-reuse channel reconstruction and\n170\tvibration recovery, while the period-limited extension of the unaliased vibration bandwidth is\n171\tquantified analytically and verified numerically.\n172\t\n173\tIndex Terms: \n174\tDistributed acoustic sensing, optical fiber sensing, cyclic-prefix-free OFDM, tail-reuse\n175\treconstruction, coherent detection.\n176\t\n177\tI Introduction\n178\t\n179\tDistributed acoustic sensing (DAS) based on coherent Rayleigh backscatter enables\n180\toptical fiber to serve not only as a transmission medium but also as a distributed array of\n181\tvibration-sensitive sensing points over large numbers of range bins. In a phase-sensitive optical\n182\ttime-domain reflectometry (ϕ\\phi-OTDR) system, an optical probe\n183\tis launched into the fiber, the weak Rayleigh backscatter is coherently detected, and dynamic strain\n184\tor vibration is inferred from the slow-time evolution of the complex backscattered field at each\n185\trange position [1, 2]. Because the sensing element is the fiber\n186\titself, DAS can use deployed or purpose-installed cables to monitor long linear assets and extended\n187\tphysical environments without placing individual electrical sensors along the path. This capability\n188\thas motivated distributed fiber-optic sensing for infrastructure, perimeter, geophysical, and\n189\tseismic monitoring applications, including demonstrations using existing dark fiber for near-surface\n190\tcharacterization and broadband event detection\n191\t[3, 4, 5, 6, 7].\n192\t\n193\tThe usefulness of DAS is determined not only by whether a vibration can be detected, but also by\n194\thow sensing range, spatial resolution, signal-to-noise ratio (SNR), and vibration bandwidth are\n195\tobtained simultaneously. These requirements are coupled. A longer fiber increases propagation\n196\tdelay, attenuation, and the temporal memory of the backscatter channel; a finer spatial resolution\n197\trequires a shorter effective impulse response or larger waveform bandwidth; a higher SNR usually\n198\trequires more optical energy, processing gain, or coherent averaging; and a higher vibration\n199\tfrequency requires faster slow-time sampling of each range cell. Therefore, a DAS waveform is not\n200\tmerely an illumination signal. It also defines the range-domain point-spread function, the amount\n201\tof useful energy per observation, the repetition period available for dynamic sampling, and the\n202\treceiver operation used to convert backscatter into a spatial trace. This coupling makes the\n203\tprobing waveform and the reconstruction receiver central design choices in long-reach,\n204\thigh-bandwidth DAS.\n205\t\n206\tConventional short-pulse DAS offers a direct and intuitive range mapping: the pulse duration sets\n207\tthe nominal spatial resolution, while the round-trip delay maps each backscatter sample to a fiber\n208\tposition. This simplicity is one reason that pulse-based ϕ\\phi-OTDR remains a widely used\n209\tarchitecture for distributed vibration sensing. However, the same mechanism also produces a basic\n210\tenergy–resolution tension. Increasing pulse width can inject more optical energy and improve SNR,\n211\tbut it broadens the spatial response; shortening the pulse improves spatial resolution, but reduces\n212\tthe available pulse energy unless the peak power is increased. In long-distance or high-bandwidth\n213\tDAS, this tradeoff becomes more severe because the system must maintain enough backscattered SNR\n214\twhile preserving spatial selectivity and refreshing each range cell fast enough for dynamic\n215\tmeasurements [3, 4].\n216\t\n217\tPulse-compression and coding techniques have been introduced to relax this tension by increasing\n218\tthe time–bandwidth product or coding gain without simply broadening the final compressed response.\n219\tEarly optical time-domain reflectometry studies used pulse-compression waveforms to improve the\n220\trange-resolved measurement process, and related ideas have been extended to phase-sensitive OTDR\n221\tfor sub-meter-resolution vibration sensing\n222\t[8, 9]. Chirped-pulse and swept-wave\n223\tapproaches further exploit frequency modulation to encode range-dependent phase or strain\n224\tinformation, while coded-pulse schemes use structured sequences to improve sensitivity and reach\n225\t[10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15].\n226\tThese developments show that waveform design is an effective way to redistribute optical energy,\n227\tbandwidth, and processing gain in DAS.\n228\t\n229\tDespite these advantages, many pulse-compression, chirped, and coded DAS receivers still recover\n230\tthe range trace through linear correlation with a known replica of the transmitted waveform. The\n231\trecovered trace is therefore the fiber channel convolved with the aperiodic waveform\n232\tautocorrelation. A narrow main lobe supports fine nominal spatial resolution, whereas sidelobes\n233\tand finite main-lobe width spread the response of one fiber section into neighboring sections. In a\n234\tdense Rayleigh backscatter channel, these off-peak correlation terms produce deterministic\n235\tinter-range leakage that remains after coherent averaging. This motivates a receiver model that\n236\ttreats the backscattered fiber as a finite-memory sensing channel and makes the effective range\n237\tresponse explicit in the reconstruction process.\n238\t\n239\tFrequency-domain channel reconstruction provides a different viewpoint. In discrete\n240\tFourier-transform OFDM, the transmitted block is synthesized from orthogonal subcarrier weights,\n241\tand a cyclic prefix (CP) is inserted so that the useful block sees the finite-memory channel as a\n242\tcircular convolution. After the discrete Fourier transform, the received sample on each active\n243\tsubcarrier is proportional to the corresponding channel frequency response. This converts a\n244\ttime-domain convolution problem into subcarrier-wise channel estimation or equalization, a principle\n245\tthat has been central to multicarrier communication systems and later optical OFDM implementations\n246\t[16, 17, 18, 19, 20, 21].\n247\t\n248\tWhen this principle is transferred from communications to DAS, the estimated channel takes on a\n249\tdifferent role. In data transmission, the channel is an impairment to be equalized; in DAS, the\n250\trange-domain Rayleigh response is itself the sensing quantity. Our preceding CP-OFDM DAS study used\n251\tknown OFDM subcarriers to estimate the active-bin channel response and reconstructed the range-domain\n252\tchannel by inverse Fourier transform [22]. The effective range response is\n253\ttherefore governed by subcarrier inversion and the active-frequency aperture rather than only by the\n254\taperiodic probe autocorrelation. This reconstruction framework also exposes a DAS-specific cost: the\n255\tCP lengthens each slow-time frame without providing an additional useful OFDM observation.\n256\t\n257\tIn DAS, the CP therefore imposes a sensing penalty. The OFDM block repetition period is the\n258\tslow-time sampling interval of every recovered range cell. At a fixed sampling rate and useful-block\n259\tlength, adding a CP lengthens each channel observation and lowers its slow-time Nyquist limit. Because\n260\tthe prefix must cover the effective fiber memory, it can occupy a substantial fraction of the probing\n261\tperiod over a long fiber. The same prefix that establishes circular convolution for frequency-domain\n262\treconstruction therefore reduces the vibration bandwidth available to each range cell.\n263\t\n264\tThis penalty is relevant to broadband, high-frequency, and high-spatial-resolution DAS\n265\t[12, 23, 15, 7]. Optical\n266\tfrequency-domain, swept/chirped, and pulse-coded approaches address these objectives through\n267\tdifferent waveform and receiver tradeoffs. Within the OFDM channel-reconstruction framework,\n268\thowever, it remains unclear whether the required circular-convolution condition can be obtained\n269\twithout an explicitly transmitted CP. Resolving this issue would retain frequency-domain channel\n270\treconstruction while avoiding prefix samples that lower the highest unaliased vibration frequency.\n271\t\n272\tHere, we investigate repeated cyclic-prefix-free OFDM (No-CP OFDM) with tail-reuse reconstruction\n273\tfor DAS. The known useful period is transmitted continuously so that the preceding-period tail\n274\tprovides the virtual cyclic extension for the current period. The receiver then estimates the\n275\tactive-bin channel response and reconstructs the range-domain channel without a separately\n276\ttransmitted prefix. Tail\n277\treuse therefore retains the CP-OFDM channel-reconstruction interpretation while shortening the\n278\tslow-time observation period.\n279\t\n280\tThe main contributions are as follows. First, we formulate a finite-memory model for repeated No-CP\n281\tOFDM DAS and identify the condition under which the received useful block follows the circular-convolution\n282\trelation required for frequency-domain channel reconstruction. Second, we connect explicit-CP\n283\toverhead to slow-time vibration bandwidth and range folding, thereby identifying when useful-period\n284\trepetition supplies the required cyclic extension. We also distinguish delay-grid sampling from\n285\tbandwidth-limited spatial resolution. Third, simulations verify the predicted range boundary and\n286\thigh-frequency vibration recovery. They further evaluate the improvement in differential-phase\n287\treliability and reconstruction SNR obtained by jointly processing fine spatial observations enabled\n288\tby bandwidth scaling at a fixed reporting interval. Finally, we implement a tail-reuse No-CP OFDM DAS\n289\treceiver and experimentally demonstrate blind localization and frequency recovery for 500-Hz and\n290\t3-kHz vibrations over a 5.2-km fiber link.\n291\t\n292\tII Principle and Signal Model\n293\t\n294\tFig. 1 summarizes the coherent ϕ\\phi-OTDR DAS architecture considered in\n295\tthis work. The section begins with a finite-memory sensing-channel model for a generic probing\n296\tsequence and shows how correlation readout determines the effective range response. It then\n297\tspecializes the probe to repeated No-CP OFDM and derives the tail-reuse circular-convolution\n298\tcondition. The resulting design discussion connects the range-validity condition to CP overhead,\n299\tslow-time vibration bandwidth, and unambiguous range, while distinguishing delay-grid sampling from\n300\tbandwidth-limited spatial resolution.\n301\t\n302\tFigure 1: A coherent DAS system used for repeated cyclic-prefix-free OFDM (No-CP OFDM) probing.\n303\tThe inset shows three repeated No-CP OFDM useful blocks without inserted CP samples. IQ: in-phase/quadrature;\n304\tEDFA: erbium-doped fiber amplifier; OF: optical filter; OC: optical circulator;\n305\tBPD: balanced photodiode; DSP: digital signal processing.\n306\t\n307\tII-A Finite-Memory DAS Channel and Effective Range Response\n308\t\n309\tThe starting point is the finite-memory sensing-channel view used in the CP-OFDM DAS precursor\n310\t[22]. Over one slow-time frame pp, the coherent Rayleigh backscatter from the\n311\tfiber is represented by the discrete range-domain channel\n312\t𝐡p=[hp​[0],hp​[1],…,hp​[M−1]]T\\mathbf{h}_{p}=[h_{p}[0],h_{p}[1],\\ldots,h_{p}[M-1]]^{\\mathrm{T}}, where MM is the number of spatial cells\n313\tcovered by the fiber under test. With sampling interval TsT_{s} and group velocity vgv_{g}, one discrete\n314\tdelay bin corresponds to the two-way spatial increment Δ​z=vg​Ts/2\\Delta z=v_{g}T_{s}/2. For a transmitted\n315\tbaseband probing sequence x​[n]x[n], the received sequence in frame pp is modeled as\n316\t\n317\typ​[n]=∑m=0M−1hp​[m]​x​[n−m]+wp​[n],y_{p}[n]=\\sum_{m=0}^{M-1}h_{p}[m]x[n-m]+w_{p}[n],\n318\t\n319\t(1)\n320\t\n321\twhere wp​[n]w_{p}[n] includes receiver noise and unmodeled impairments. The vibration-induced phase\n322\tvariation is embedded in the slow-time evolution of hp​[m]h_{p}[m].\n323\t\n324\tThis model also clarifies the effective range response of conventional correlation-based DAS. If a\n325\tfinite-duration probing waveform s​[n]s[n] is recovered through linear correlation with its known\n326\treplica, let rs​[ℓ]r_{s}[\\ell] denote its aperiodic autocorrelation, Es=rs​[0]E_{s}=r_{s}[0] its energy, and\n327\tcs​[ℓ]=rs​[ℓ]/Esc_{s}[\\ell]=r_{s}[\\ell]/E_{s} its normalized autocorrelation response. The energy-normalized\n328\tmatched-filter estimate at range bin ℓ\\ell can then be written as\n329\t\n330\th^pMF​[ℓ]\\displaystyle\\hat{h}^{\\mathrm{MF}}_{p}[\\ell]\n331\t\n332\t=∑m=0M−1hp​[m]​cs​[ℓ−m]+ν~p​[ℓ]\\displaystyle=\\sum_{m=0}^{M-1}h_{p}[m]c_{s}[\\ell-m]+\\tilde{\\nu}_{p}[\\ell]\n333\t\n334\t(2)\n335\t\n336\t=hp​[ℓ]+∑m=0m≠ℓM−1hp​[m]​cs​[ℓ−m]+ν~p​[ℓ].\\displaystyle=h_{p}[\\ell]+\\sum_{\\begin{subarray}{c}m=0\\\\\n337\tm\\neq\\ell\\end{subarray}}^{M-1}h_{p}[m]c_{s}[\\ell-m]+\\tilde{\\nu}_{p}[\\ell].\n338\t\n339\tThe summation term in (2) is the waveform-dependent leakage term: range bins\n340\tother than ℓ\\ell enter the recovered bin through the off-peak samples of cs​[ℓ]c_{s}[\\ell]. A finer\n341\tanalog-to-digital converter (ADC) grid may represent this point-spread function with more samples,\n342\tbut it does not change the underlying autocorrelation-weighted response. The prior CP-OFDM\n343\tframework instead forms a circular-convolution observation, estimates the loaded frequency bins,\n344\tand transforms them back to the range domain [22]. Its effective range kernel\n345\tis determined by the subcarrier inversion and active-frequency weighting. The present repeated\n346\tNo-CP work keeps this reconstruction view but replaces the explicitly transmitted cyclic prefix\n347\twith useful-symbol repetition.\n348\t\n349\tII-B Repeated No-CP OFDM Tail-Reuse Reconstruction\n350\t\n351\tLet NN denote the OFDM useful-symbol length and let S​[k]S[k] be the known complex weight on the\n352\tkkth subcarrier. One useful OFDM period is\n353\t\n354\ts​[n]=1N​∑k=0N−1S​[k]​ej​2​π​k​n/N,0≤n<N.s[n]=\\frac{1}{N}\\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}S[k]e^{j2\\pi kn/N},\\quad 0\\leq n<N.\n355\t\n356\t(3)\n357\t\n358\tIn the proposed repeated No-CP sensing waveform, no cyclic prefix, cyclic suffix, or zero guard is inserted.\n359\tInstead, the same known useful OFDM period is transmitted continuously,\n360\t\n361\tx​[n]=s​[⟨n⟩N],x​[n+N]=x​[n],x[n]=s[\\langle n\\rangle_{N}],\\quad x[n+N]=x[n],\n362\t\n363\t(4)\n364\t\n365\twhere ⟨n⟩N\\langle n\\rangle_{N} denotes the integer nn modulo NN.\n366\t\n367\tThe corresponding timing relation is illustrated in Fig. 2. Unlike\n368\tconventional CP-OFDM, the highlighted tail is not a newly inserted guard interval; it is already part\n369\tof the preceding useful OFDM period in the continuous transmitted stream. At the receiver, this tail\n370\tis used as the virtual cyclic extension associated with the current useful period before channel\n371\treconstruction based on the fast Fourier transform (FFT) and frequency-domain equalization (FDE).\n372\t\n373\tFigure 2: Principle of virtual-CP construction in repeated No-CP OFDM with tail reuse. The\n374\ttransmitted stream contains only repeated useful OFDM blocks. The tail of useful block n−1n-1 is reused at the receiver\n375\tas the virtual CP for useful block nn, after which the useful block is processed by FFT/FDE. FFT: fast Fourier\n376\ttransform; FDE: frequency-domain equalization.\n377\t\n378\tThe key observation formalized below is that a repeated useful period provides a virtual cyclic\n379\textension. For the current period, the last M−1M-1 samples of the previous period are identical to\n380\tthe samples that would have been copied into an explicit cyclic prefix. Thus no additional prefix\n381\tsamples are transmitted, but the linear fiber convolution can still be observed as a circular\n382\tconvolution when the repeated period covers the channel memory. Under the range condition\n383\t\n384\tN≥M,N\\geq M,\n385\t\n386\t(5)\n387\t\n388\tand assuming that the channel is approximately constant over the previous-tail-plus-current-useful\n389\tobservation interval, an aligned NN-sample receive window becomes\n390\t\n391\tup​[n]=∑m=0M−1hp​[m]​s​[⟨n−m⟩N]+wp​[n],0≤n<N.u_{p}[n]=\\sum_{m=0}^{M-1}h_{p}[m]s[\\langle n-m\\rangle_{N}]+w_{p}[n],\\quad 0\\leq n<N.\n392\t\n393\t(6)\n394\t\n395\tEquation (6) is the theoretical bridge from sufficient-CP OFDM to repeated\n396\tNo-CP OFDM: the circular-convolution condition is preserved by repeating the known useful period,\n397\twhile the explicit CP is removed from the transmitted stream.\n398\t\n399\tTaking the NN-point discrete Fourier transform (DFT) of (6) gives\n400\t\n401\tUp​[k]\\displaystyle U_{p}[k]\n402\t\n403\t=S​[k]​Hp​[k]+Wp​[k],\\displaystyle=S[k]H_{p}[k]+W_{p}[k],\n404\t\n405\t(7)\n406\t\n407\tHp​[k]\\displaystyle H_{p}[k]\n408\t\n409\t=∑m=0M−1hp​[m]​e−j​2​π​k​m/N.\\displaystyle=\\sum_{m=0}^{M-1}h_{p}[m]e^{-j2\\pi km/N}.\n410\t\n411\tFor active subcarriers k∈𝒦k\\in\\mathcal{K}, the channel spectrum is estimated by one-tap\n412\tregularized least squares (LS),\n413\t\n414\tH^p​[k]={Up​[k]​S∗​[k]|S​[k]|2+λ,k∈𝒦,0,k∉𝒦,\\hat{H}_{p}[k]=\\begin{cases}\\dfrac{U_{p}[k]S^{*}[k]}{|S[k]|^{2}+\\lambda},&k\\in\\mathcal{K},\\\\[5.69054pt]\n415\t0,&k\\notin\\mathcal{K},\\end{cases}\n416\t\n417\t(8)\n418\t\n419\twhere λ\\lambda controls noise enhancement near weak loaded subcarriers. The case λ=0\\lambda=0\n420\tcorresponds to zero-forcing (ZF) inversion on the active set. The range-domain channel estimate is\n421\tthen obtained by inverse DFT,\n422\t\n423\th^p​[m]=1N​∑k=0N−1H^p​[k]​ej​2​π​k​m/N,0≤m<M.\\hat{h}_{p}[m]=\\frac{1}{N}\\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\\hat{H}_{p}[k]e^{j2\\pi km/N},\\quad 0\\leq m<M.\n424\t\n425\t(9)\n426\t\n427\tThe effective range response follows directly from\n428\t(7)–(9). Define the deterministic frequency-domain\n429\tweighting as Gλ​[k]G_{\\lambda}[k]. Then\n430\t\n431\tGλ​[k]\\displaystyle G_{\\lambda}[k]\n432\t\n433\t={|S​[k]|2|S​[k]|2+λ,k∈𝒦,0,k∉𝒦,\\displaystyle=\n434\t\n435\t(10)\n436\t\n437\tgλ​[m]\\displaystyle g_{\\lambda}[m]\n438\t\n439\t=1N​∑k=0N−1Gλ​[k]​ej​2​π​k​m/N,\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{N}\\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}G_{\\lambda}[k]e^{j2\\pi km/N},\n440\t\n441\th^p​[m]\\displaystyle\\hat{h}_{p}[m]\n442\t\n443\t=∑q=0M−1hp​[q]​gλ​[⟨m−q⟩N]+w~p,λ​[m].\\displaystyle=\\sum_{q=0}^{M-1}h_{p}[q]g_{\\lambda}[\\langle m-q\\rangle_{N}]+\\tilde{w}_{p,\\lambda}[m].\n444\t\n445\tHere gλ​[m]g_{\\lambda}[m] is the circular point-spread function, and\n446\tw~p,λ​[m]\\tilde{w}_{p,\\lambda}[m] is the correspondingly weighted noise. Equation (10)\n447\tprovides a common description of full-bin reconstruction, inactive subcarriers, and regularization.\n448\t\n449\tProposition 1 (tail reuse for repeated No-CP reconstruction): Suppose that the same useful\n450\tOFDM period is repeated, N≥MN\\geq M, the receiver window is aligned to a consistent periodic windowing\n451\tphase, and the channel is quasi-static over the effective previous-tail-plus-current-useful\n452\tobservation interval. In the ideal full-bin case with S​[k]≠0S[k]\\neq 0 for all kk and λ=0\\lambda=0, the\n453\tZF reconstruction in (9) gives\n454\t\n455\th^p​[m]=hp​[m]+w~p​[m],0≤m<M,\\hat{h}_{p}[m]=h_{p}[m]+\\tilde{w}_{p}[m],\\quad 0\\leq m<M,\n456\t\n457\t(11)\n458\t\n459\twhere w~p​[m]\\tilde{w}_{p}[m] represents receiver noise after frequency-domain inversion and IDFT. If the noise term is absent,\n460\th^p​[m]=hp​[m]\\hat{h}_{p}[m]=h_{p}[m] on the DFT delay grid, and no deterministic contribution from q≠mq\\neq m range\n461\tbins remains.\n462\t\n463\tTo see this, we substitute the definition of Hp​[k]H_{p}[k] in (7) into\n464\t(9) with λ=0\\lambda=0 and full nonzero subcarrier loading, and obtain\n465\t\n466\th^p​[m]=∑q=0M−1hp​[q]​[1N​∑k=0N−1ej​2​π​k​(m−q)/N]+w~p​[m].\\hat{h}_{p}[m]=\\sum_{q=0}^{M-1}h_{p}[q]\\left[\\frac{1}{N}\\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}e^{j2\\pi k(m-q)/N}\\right]+\\tilde{w}_{p}[m].\n467\t\n468\t(12)\n469\t\n470\tThe bracketed sum evaluates to δN​[m−q]\\delta_{N}[m-q], the Kronecker delta on an NN-periodic delay grid.\n471\tOn the physical fiber support, the condition N≥MN\\geq M prevents modular wraparound between two\n472\tdifferent range bins, so δN​[m−q]\\delta_{N}[m-q] acts as an ordinary Kronecker delta. The first term in\n473\t(12) is therefore hp​[m]h_{p}[m]. The key distinction from explicit-CP OFDM is not\n474\tthe frequency-domain estimator itself, but the origin of the cyclic extension. Here it is supplied\n475\tby tail reuse of the preceding repeated period rather than by newly transmitted prefix samples. For\n476\tconstant-modulus full-bin loading, the zero-regularization estimator in\n477\t(8) is, up to a constant scale, mathematically equivalent to circular matched\n478\tfiltering. Exact discrete-channel recovery then follows because the cyclic autocorrelation is a\n479\tKronecker delta. With inactive bins or regularization, the effective response is instead\n480\tgλ​[m]g_{\\lambda}[m] in (10).\n481\t\n482\tThe DAS vibration readout is obtained from the reconstructed channel through gauge-differential\n483\tphase processing. For a gauge separation of GG samples, the complex gauge product and its phase\n484\tchange relative to a reference frame p=0p=0 are\n485\t\n486\tg^p​[m]\\displaystyle\\hat{g}_{p}[m]\n487\t\n488\t=h^p​[m+G]​h^p∗​[m],0≤m<M−G,\\displaystyle=\\hat{h}_{p}[m+G]\\hat{h}_{p}^{*}[m],\\quad 0\\leq m<M-G,\n489\t\n490\t(13)\n491\t\n492\tΔ​ϕp​[m]\\displaystyle\\Delta\\phi_{p}[m]\n493\t\n494\t=∠​{g^p​[m]​g^0∗​[m]}.\\displaystyle=\\angle\\left\\{\\hat{g}_{p}[m]\\hat{g}_{0}^{*}[m]\\right\\}.\n495\t\n496\tThis operation converts slow-time changes in the reconstructed Rayleigh channel into local vibration\n497\ttraces along the fiber.\n498\t\n499\tII-C Design Consequences: Overhead, Vibration Bandwidth, and Range\n500\t\n501\tThe repeated No-CP model links cyclic-extension overhead, slow-time sampling, and range validity in\n502\tDAS operation. For a conventional CP-OFDM sensing waveform using the same useful-symbol length NN,\n503\ta sufficient CP must cover the finite channel memory,\n504\t\n505\tLCP≥M−1.L_{\\mathrm{CP}}\\geq M-1.\n506\t\n507\t(14)\n508\t\n509\tThe corresponding CP-OFDM and No-CP repetition periods are\n510\t\n511\tTCP=(N+LCP)​Ts,TNoCP=N​Ts.T_{\\mathrm{CP}}=(N+L_{\\mathrm{CP}})T_{s},\\quad T_{\\mathrm{NoCP}}=NT_{s}.\n512\t\n513\t(15)\n514\t\n515\tThus the useful-symbol-normalized CP overhead is LCP/NL_{\\mathrm{CP}}/N, and the fraction of a\n516\tsufficient-CP frame occupied by CP samples is LCP/(N+LCP)L_{\\mathrm{CP}}/(N+L_{\\mathrm{CP}}). The No-CP\n517\twaveform does not remove the physical requirement that the channel memory be covered; instead, it\n518\treuses the previous repeated useful-period tail as the virtual cyclic extension.\n519\t\n520\tThe second consequence is an increase in the slow-time sampling rate relative to an explicit-CP\n521\timplementation with the same NN and fiber memory. Since DAS vibration recovery samples the channel\n522\tonce per repeated probing period, the highest unaliased vibration frequency is bounded by\n523\t\n524\tfmax=12​Trep.f_{\\max}=\\frac{1}{2T_{\\mathrm{rep}}}.\n525\t\n526\t(16)\n527\t\n528\tTherefore,\n529\t\n530\tfmaxNoCPfmaxCP=TCPTNoCP=1+LCPN.\\frac{f_{\\max}^{\\mathrm{NoCP}}}{f_{\\max}^{\\mathrm{CP}}}=\\frac{T_{\\mathrm{CP}}}{T_{\\mathrm{NoCP}}}=1+\\frac{L_{\\mathrm{CP}}}{N}.\n531\t\n532\t(17)\n533\t\n534\tThe range-validity condition further links fiber length to slow-time bandwidth. Because\n535\tTNoCP=N​TsT_{\\mathrm{NoCP}}=NT_{s} and N≥MN\\geq M,\n536\t\n537\tTNoCP≥M​Ts≈2​Lvg,fmaxNoCP≲vg4​L,T_{\\mathrm{NoCP}}\\geq MT_{s}\\approx\\frac{2L}{v_{g}},\\quad f_{\\max}^{\\mathrm{NoCP}}\\lesssim\\frac{v_{g}}{4L},\n538\t\n539\t(18)\n540\t\n541\twhere LL is the fiber length. The round-trip propagation time therefore sets a lower bound on the\n542\tvalid useful-period duration and an upper bound on the unaliased vibration frequency. By eliminating\n543\ta separately transmitted prefix, tail reuse allows repeated No-CP OFDM to approach this\n544\tlength-constrained limit. Nevertheless, the useful period must still span the full fiber round-trip\n545\tmemory to avoid range folding.\n546\t\n547\tFor a minimum-sufficient explicit-CP reference, substituting\n548\tLCP≥M−1L_{\\mathrm{CP}}\\geq M-1 into (17) gives the\n549\tperiod penalty needed to accommodate the same fiber memory. For completeness, if a CP-OFDM sensing\n550\timplementation additionally inserts a guard or idle interval of LgL_{\\mathrm{g}} samples between\n551\tprobing blocks, its repetition period and the corresponding vibration-bandwidth ratio become\n552\t\n553\tTCP,rep=(N+LCP+Lg)​Ts,fmaxNoCPfmaxCP,rep=N+LCP+LgN.T_{\\mathrm{CP,rep}}=(N+L_{\\mathrm{CP}}+L_{\\mathrm{g}})T_{s},\\quad\\frac{f_{\\max}^{\\mathrm{NoCP}}}{f_{\\max}^{\\mathrm{CP,rep}}}=\\frac{N+L_{\\mathrm{CP}}+L_{\\mathrm{g}}}{N}.\n554\t\n555\t(19)\n556\t\n557\tEquation (19) generalizes the period comparison; the continuous CP-OFDM\n558\treference used in Section III corresponds to Lg=0L_{\\mathrm{g}}=0.\n559\t\n560\tThe same design variables also set the unambiguous circular-deconvolution range,\n561\t\n562\tΔ​z=vg​Ts2=vg2​Fs,Ramb=N​Δ​z.\\Delta z=\\frac{v_{g}T_{s}}{2}=\\frac{v_{g}}{2F_{s}},\\quad R_{\\mathrm{amb}}=N\\Delta z.\n563\t\n564\t(20)\n565\t\n566\tHere Δ​z\\Delta z is the DFT delay-grid sampling interval. The useful-block length must be\n567\tchosen so that RambR_{\\mathrm{amb}} exceeds the physical fiber support; any excess unambiguous range is a\n568\trange-validity margin rather than a spatial-resolution gain. The physical resolving interval is instead\n569\tset by the occupied frequency aperture,\n570\t\n571\tBocc=Nact​Δ​f,Δ​zres≈vg2​Bocc,B_{\\mathrm{occ}}=N_{\\mathrm{act}}\\Delta f,\\quad\\Delta z_{\\mathrm{res}}\\approx\\frac{v_{g}}{2B_{\\mathrm{occ}}},\n572\t\n573\t(21)\n574\t\n575\twhere NactN_{\\mathrm{act}} is the number of active subcarriers and Δ​f\\Delta f is the subcarrier\n576\tspacing. Thus the DFT delay-grid sampling interval, the unambiguous periodic range, and the\n577\tbandwidth-limited resolving interval are related but distinct quantities.\n578\t\n579\tBandwidth expansion must be considered jointly with the processing rate and useful-block length. A\n580\twider probing band generally requires a higher complex-baseband processing rate Fs=1/TsF_{s}=1/T_{s}, and the\n581\tresulting finer delay grid increases the discrete channel memory according to\n582\t\n583\tM≈2​L​Fsvg.M\\approx\\frac{2LF_{s}}{v_{g}}.\n584\t\n585\t(22)\n586\t\n587\tThe useful-block length must therefore increase with FsF_{s} to preserve\n588\tN/Fs≥2​L/vgN/F_{s}\\geq 2L/v_{g}. Scaling NN and FsF_{s} proportionally leaves the useful-period duration,\n589\tunambiguous sensing range, slow-time sampling rate, and vibration Nyquist limit unchanged. Because\n590\tthe minimum valid useful-period duration is constrained by the fiber round-trip memory, this\n591\tproportional scaling does not provide a further increase in the slow-time Nyquist limit. The\n592\tadditional occupied bandwidth is instead expressed as a finer intrinsic spatial resolving interval.\n593\t\n594\tIf the output interval is deliberately held coarser than this intrinsic resolution, a reported\n595\tspatial unit contains multiple resolvable fine-grid observations. Their nominal ratio is\n596\t\n597\tρB=BoccBtar,Btar≈vg2​Δ​ztar,\\rho_{B}=\\frac{B_{\\mathrm{occ}}}{B_{\\mathrm{tar}}},\\quad B_{\\mathrm{tar}}\\approx\\frac{v_{g}}{2\\Delta z_{\\mathrm{tar}}},\n598\t\n599\t(23)\n600\t\n601\twhere Δ​ztar\\Delta z_{\\mathrm{tar}} is the target effective spatial resolution and BtarB_{\\mathrm{tar}}\n602\tis the bandwidth required to support that resolution. Here, ρB\\rho_{B} characterizes the available\n603\tspatial sampling ratio, not the number of statistically independent observations, because adjacent\n604\tgauge-phase traces can remain correlated. Fine-grid traces with locally consistent slow-time\n605\tresponses may be gain-aligned and combined within each reporting cell without temporal averaging,\n606\twhich can reduce sensitivity to individual Rayleigh fading nulls while preserving the frame rate.\n607\tThe gain depends on power normalization, receiver noise bandwidth, fading statistics, and\n608\tinter-trace correlation. This processing opportunity is not unique to repeated No-CP OFDM; tail reuse\n609\tallows it to be retained without adding CP-induced slow-time overhead.\n610\t\n611\tII-D Validity Boundary and Practical Interpretation\n612\t\n613\tThe repeated No-CP principle requires the same known OFDM useful period to be transmitted\n614\tcontinuously. If the useful period\n615\tchanges from frame to frame, the previous period tail is no longer the cyclic continuation of the\n616\tcurrent period and (6) no longer follows. The channel must also be\n617\tquasi-static over the effective previous-tail-plus-useful observation interval.\n618\t\n619\tThe period-length condition in (5) defines the most important failure\n620\tmode. If N<MN<M, the receiver cannot uniquely assign all physical ranges to one DFT delay grid. The\n621\tperiodic deconvolution then recovers a folded channel,\n622\t\n623\thp,fold​[r]=∑ℓ:r+ℓ​N<Mhp​[r+ℓ​N],0≤r<N,h_{p,\\mathrm{fold}}[r]=\\sum_{\\ell:\\,r+\\ell N<M}h_{p}[r+\\ell N],\\quad 0\\leq r<N,\n624\t\n625\t(24)\n626\t\n627\tso scatterers or perturbations separated by integer multiples of N​Δ​zN\\Delta z contribute to the same\n628\treconstructed bin. This folding is a range ambiguity of the periodic probing waveform, not a\n629\treceiver implementation artifact.\n630\t\n631\tEven when N≥MN\\geq M, the receiver must select a periodic windowing phase that maps the circularly\n632\treconstructed channel to the physical fiber span. When N>MN>M and the expected physical support is\n633\tknown, a useful timing metric is the ratio between reconstructed energy inside that support and\n634\tresidual energy in the circular tail,\n635\t\n636\tη​(q)=∑m=0M−1|h^p,q​[m]|2∑m=MN−1|h^p,q​[m]|2+ϵ,\\eta(q)=\\frac{\\sum_{m=0}^{M-1}|\\hat{h}_{p,q}[m]|^{2}}{\\sum_{m=M}^{N-1}|\\hat{h}_{p,q}[m]|^{2}+\\epsilon},\n637\t\n638\t(25)\n639\t\n640\twhere qq denotes a candidate window start and ϵ\\epsilon prevents division by zero. Maximizing\n641\tη​(q)\\eta(q) favors the alignment in which the reconstructed channel energy lies within the physical\n642\tfiber span rather than wrapping into the unused DFT tail.\n643\t\n644\tWith edge guards, DC nulling, transmitter and receiver frequency responses, active-bin\n645\tregularization, and finite SNR, the practical reconstruction is a band-limited and regularized\n646\tchannel estimate. A grid-aligned point scatterer can be reconstructed as a Kronecker-delta response\n647\ton the DFT delay grid under Proposition 1, but an off-grid scatterer or a\n648\treduced active-frequency aperture produces a finite-bandwidth Dirichlet- or windowed-sinc-like\n649\tresponse whose first-null scale is governed by 1/Bocc1/B_{\\mathrm{occ}}. The proposed repeated No-CP scheme\n650\tuses periodic circular deconvolution to remove explicit CP overhead and increase the slow-time\n651\tsampling rate under the stated range and timing conditions, while the spatial resolution remains\n652\tgoverned by the occupied bandwidth.\n653\t\n654\tFigure 3: Transmitter and receiver DSP flow used in the repeated No-CP OFDM DAS simulation, from waveform\n655\tgeneration to gauge-differential phase recovery. PRBS: pseudo-random binary sequence;\n656\tQPSK: quadrature phase-shift keying; IFFT: inverse fast Fourier transform;\n657\tFFT: fast Fourier transform; FDE: frequency-domain equalization.\n658\t\n659\tIII Numerical Simulation\n660\t\n661\tNumerical simulations first examine the signal-model predictions in Section II\n662\tbefore the experimental test. They isolate the mechanism and boundary of the proposed repeated\n663\tNo-CP tail-reuse reconstruction. The simulations first test the range\n664\tcondition: whether the repeated useful OFDM period provides the virtual cyclic extension required\n665\tfor channel reconstruction when N≥MN\\geq M, and how the reconstruction fails when this condition is\n666\tviolated. Dynamic perturbation recovery then examines whether the same reconstruction chain can\n667\tsupport DAS vibration readout under the modeled conditions. As a secondary design study, bandwidth\n668\tscaling is examined at a fixed reporting interval.\n669\t\n670\tThe simulated transmitter and receiver digital signal processing (DSP) chain is summarized in\n671\tFig. 3. The transmitter maps a known pseudo-random binary sequence to quadrature\n672\tphase-shift keying (QPSK) symbols, generates the OFDM useful period, and repeats it without inserting\n673\texplicit CP samples. The receiver samples the backscattered signal, forms the virtual-CP observation\n674\tdescribed in Section II-B, estimates the channel in the frequency domain,\n675\ttransforms it back to range, and obtains the DAS phase map through gauge-differential processing.\n676\t\n677\tIII-A Simulation Configuration\n678\t\n679\tThe simulated link contains 5.2 km of sensing fiber, corresponding to an approximately\n680\t52-μ\\mus round-trip channel memory. The reference OFDM bandwidth is set to 75 MHz, the\n681\tcomplex-baseband sampling rate is 75 MSa/s, and the useful-block length is 4096 samples.\n682\tThis combination gives a 54.61-μ\\mus useful period, a 5.46-km unambiguous reconstruction span,\n683\tand a 1.333-m range-bin spacing. The corresponding channel memory is 3900 samples, so the useful\n684\tperiod slightly exceeds the physical fiber support. The same known OFDM useful block is transmitted\n685\tperiodically without an explicit CP, cyclic suffix, or zero guard, and the preceding-period tail\n686\tprovides the virtual prefix used by the receiver.\n687\t\n688\tUnless otherwise stated, the tail-reuse, range-condition, and dynamic simulations use this 75-MHz\n689\tconfiguration. The bandwidth-scaling study in\n690\tSection III-D instead varies the occupied bandwidth while\n691\tscaling the useful-block length proportionally.\n692\t\n693\tThe fiber backscatter is represented by a dense complex Rayleigh channel whose slow-time phase is\n694\tlocally perturbed by prescribed vibration events. The channel is held constant within each OFDM\n695\tperiod and updated at the slow-time sampling instants. Additive receiver noise is included before\n696\tfrequency-domain channel estimation. After FFT-domain deconvolution and inverse FFT reconstruction,\n697\tthe recovered range-domain channel is converted into vibration traces through gauge-differential\n698\tphase processing. Table I summarizes the parameters used for the\n699\ttail-reuse, range-condition, and dynamic simulations.\n700\t\n701\tThe nominal and shortened-period configurations test the valid and folded range conditions,\n702\trespectively. In the nominal case, N=4096>M=3900N=4096>M=3900; the shortened-period case retains the same\n703\treconstruction chain while deliberately violating this condition.\n704\t\n705\tThe continuous CP-OFDM reference used in the dynamic simulations transmits explicit-CP OFDM blocks\n706\tback to back. It uses the same 4096-sample useful block, prepends a 3899-sample CP, and removes the\n707\tCP before FFT-domain channel estimation. The otherwise matched reconstruction conditions isolate\n708\tthe change in slow-time probing period introduced by the explicit CP.\n709\t\n710\tTABLE I: Parameters for the Tail-Reuse and Dynamic DAS Simulations\n711\t\n712\tParameter\n713\t\n714\tValue or setting\n715\t\n716\tFiber length\n717\t\n718\t5.2 km\n719\t\n720\tReference OFDM bandwidth\n721\t\n722\t75 MHz\n723\t\n724\tSampling rate\n725\t\n726\t75 MSa/s\n727\t\n728\tRange-bin spacing\n729\t\n730\t1.333 m\n731\t\n732\tEffective channel memory\n733\t\n734\t3900 samples\n735\t\n736\tGauge length\n737\t\n738\t2.667 m\n739\t\n740\tOFDM useful length\n741\t\n742\t4096 samples\n743\t\n744\tUnambiguous reconstruction range\n745\t\n746\t5.46 km\n747\t\n748\tNo-CP explicit CP length\n749\t\n750\t0 samples\n751\t\n752\tVirtual prefix length\n753\t\n754\t3899 samples\n755\t\n756\tNo-CP useful-period duration\n757\t\n758\t54.61 μ\\mus\n759\t\n760\tNo-CP slow-time frames\n761\t\n762\t150\n763\t\n764\tNo-CP Nyquist limit\n765\t\n766\t9.16 kHz\n767\t\n768\tReceiver SNR\n769\t\n770\t45 dB\n771\t\n772\tCP-OFDM explicit CP length\n773\t\n774\t3899 samples\n775\t\n776\tCP-OFDM block period\n777\t\n778\t106.60 μ\\mus\n779\t\n780\tCP-OFDM frames\n781\t\n782\t77 over the same 8.137-ms window\n783\t\n784\tCP-OFDM Nyquist limit\n785\t\n786\t4.69 kHz\n787\t\n788\tIII-B Tail-Reuse and Range-Condition Verification\n789\t\n790\tThe first simulation directly tests the range condition behind the virtual-CP reconstruction.\n791\tSeven perturbation events are placed along the\n792\t5.2-km fiber so that the reconstruction must assign responses over nearly the entire sensing span.\n793\tThe event positions are 0.65, 1.65, 2.20, 2.60, 3.00, 3.85, and 5.00 km, and\n794\tthe corresponding vibration frequencies are 500, 650, 800, 950, 1100, 1250, and\n795\t1400 Hz, with the same 1-rad phase-modulation amplitude. The plotted traces in\n796\tFig. 4 are single-block spatial snapshots selected from the\n797\t109th repeated OFDM block, i.e., the 109th slow-time frame of a 150-frame simulation sequence.\n798\tIn the valid configuration, N=4096N=4096 and M=3900M=3900, so the useful OFDM period is long enough to cover\n799\tthe effective fiber memory. The tail of the preceding useful period can therefore supply the cyclic\n800\textension required by the current receive window, and the expected outcome is a spatial response\n801\tlocalized at the physical event positions.\n802\t\n803\tFigure 4: Numerical comparison of valid repeated No-CP tail-reuse reconstruction and invalid N<MN<M\n804\trange folding. (a) When the useful period covers the fiber memory, events E1–E7 remain localized\n805\tover the 5.2-km span. (b) With a 3.2-km unambiguous range, the response from the 3.2–5.2-km fiber\n806\tsection folds into the reconstructed 0–2.0-km interval, while output beyond 3.2 km has no unique\n807\tphysical-range interpretation. Both panels show the spatial differential-phase snapshot of the\n808\t109th repeated OFDM block.\n809\t\n810\tFigure 4(a) follows this prediction. The labeled events\n811\tE1–E7 are recovered at their prescribed distances, while the inter-event regions remain close to\n812\tthe background level. This behavior is the numerical counterpart of\n813\t(6): after virtual-CP construction, the receiver observes an effective\n814\tcircular convolution over the physical fiber support and can reconstruct the range-domain channel by\n815\tFFT-domain deconvolution and inverse FFT processing.\n816\t\n817\tThe same figure also shows the failure mode when the condition N≥MN\\geq M is deliberately violated.\n818\tIn this invalid case, a short-period branch with Nfold<MN_{\\mathrm{fold}}<M is used, giving a 3.2-km\n819\tmaximum unambiguous range that is smaller than the 5.2-km fiber length. As predicted by\n820\t(24), the complex channel response from the physical 3.2–5.2-km section folds\n821\tinto the reconstructed 0–2.0-km interval. Gauge-differential phase is calculated after this\n822\tcomplex-channel superposition, so the resulting cross terms distort the phase response within the\n823\tpreceding range interval instead of producing simply shifted event replicas. Output beyond 3.2 km\n824\tlies outside the valid reconstruction range and therefore has no unique physical-range interpretation.\n825\t\n826\tFigure 5: Distance–frequency detection map for the 100-event repeated No-CP OFDM DAS simulation.\n827\tThe score combines median-normalized slow-time spectral magnitude with square-root-weighted spatial\n828\troot-mean-square phase activity. White circles mark the prescribed event coordinates from 50 m to\n829\t5150 m and from 800 Hz to 8800 Hz.\n830\t\n831\tIII-C Dynamic Sensing and Slow-Time Bandwidth\n832\t\n833\tAfter the range condition has been tested, the same reconstruction chain is applied to dynamic\n834\tperturbation scenes. A 100-event scene is used here to check whether the tail-reuse receiver can\n835\trecover a dense set of simultaneous vibration responses over the full sensing span. The vibration\n836\tpositions are uniformly distributed from 50 m to 5150 m, and the vibration frequencies are\n837\tuniformly swept from 800 Hz to 8800 Hz. All events have the same 0.5-rad phase-modulation\n838\tamplitude with random initial phases. The tail-reuse No-CP reconstruction uses 150 slow-time frames\n839\tand gives an 8.137-ms monitoring window. This frequency range remains below the 9.16-kHz No-CP slow-time\n840\tNyquist limit. For comparison, the continuous CP-OFDM reference follows the schedule defined in\n841\tSection III-A. It provides 77 slow-time samples over the same\n842\tmonitoring window, with a 106.60-μ\\mus block period and a 4.69-kHz Nyquist limit.\n843\t\n844\tFigure 5 presents the reconstructed scene in the\n845\tdistance–frequency plane. At each distance cell, the slow-time spectral magnitude is normalized by\n846\tits non-DC median and weighted by the square root of the normalized spatial root-mean-square phase\n847\tactivity. The resulting score is normalized to its global maximum for visualization. The bright\n848\tnarrowband responses follow the 100 prescribed distance–frequency coordinates across the full\n849\t5.2-km span. Their alignment with the preset markers shows that the tail-reuse receiver preserves\n850\tthe joint range and frequency assignment of the simulated events, consistent with the valid range\n851\tcondition in Fig. 4.\n852\t\n853\tThe joint distance–frequency result in Fig. 5 is then\n854\texamined in the slow-time domain through representative traces.\n855\tFigure 6 compares\n856\tfour events selected from the same 100-event simulation. For the events near 0.8 kHz and 3.5 kHz,\n857\tboth the No-CP tail-reuse receiver and the continuous CP-OFDM reference remain below the CP-OFDM\n858\tNyquist limit, so the displayed waveforms are close. For the events near 6.1 kHz and 8.8 kHz,\n859\thowever, the continuous CP-OFDM slow-time sampling rate is below the requirement and the displayed\n860\twaveforms appear at the corresponding aliased frequencies. The No-CP traces continue to follow the\n861\thigh-frequency oscillations because the useful-block repetition period provides the larger\n862\tslow-time sampling rate.\n863\t\n864\tFigure 6: Recovered vibration waveforms for representative events in the 100-event simulation.\n865\tThe No-CP tail-reuse result is compared with the continuous CP-OFDM reference over a 2-ms\n866\tslow-time window. The panel titles list the event position, prescribed vibration frequency, and\n867\tcontinuous CP-OFDM alias frequency.\n868\t\n869\tThe same trend is summarized in the frequency domain in Fig. 7.\n870\tThe recovered dominant frequency is plotted against\n871\tthe prescribed vibration frequency for 50 representative events selected from the 100-event scene.\n872\tThe No-CP tail-reuse result follows the ideal no-alias relation across the 800-Hz to 8800-Hz\n873\tfrequency span. By contrast, the continuous CP-OFDM result follows the ideal line only below its\n874\t4.69-kHz Nyquist limit and then folds to lower recovered frequencies. This frequency-domain view is\n875\tconsistent with the waveform examples in Fig. 6 and shows\n876\tthat the high-frequency recovery is a consequence of the larger slow-time sampling rate provided by\n877\tthe repeated useful OFDM period.\n878\t\n879\tFigure 7: Recovered vibration frequency versus prescribed vibration frequency for 50 representative\n880\tevents selected from the 100-event simulation. The dotted vertical line marks the continuous\n881\tCP-OFDM Nyquist limit.\n882\t\n883\tIII-D Bandwidth Scaling at a Fixed Reporting Interval\n884\t\n885\tFor this design study, the occupied bandwidth is increased from 75 MHz to 150, 225, and 300 MHz,\n886\twith the receiver processing rate increased correspondingly from 75 MSa/s to 150, 225, and\n887\t300 MSa/s. The useful-block length is scaled proportionally from 4096 samples to 8192, 12288, and\n888\t16384 samples. The useful-period\n889\tduration, unambiguous sensing range, slow-time sampling rate, and final reporting interval therefore\n890\tremain fixed, while the reconstructed range response is sampled on progressively finer spatial\n891\tgrids. Locally consistent fine-grid gauge-phase observations are then combined within each reporting\n892\tcell without temporal averaging.\n893\t\n894\tFor the reliability distribution in Fig. 8(a), an\n895\teffective differential-phase reliability is used as a mechanism-level diagnostic. Let hih_{i} and\n896\thi+Gh_{i+G} denote two complex Rayleigh channel samples separated by the gauge spacing GG. The\n897\tsingle fine-sample reliability, the joint reliability of reporting cell 𝒞j\\mathcal{C}_{j}, and the\n898\tnormalized dB quantity plotted in Fig. 8(a) are defined as\n899\t\n900\tri=|hi|2​|hi+G|2|hi|2+|hi+G|2+ϵ,Rj(ρB)=∑i∈𝒞jri,ηj(ρB)=10​log10⁡Rj(ρB)medianj⁡Rj(1).\\begin{gathered}r_{i}=\\frac{|h_{i}|^{2}|h_{i+G}|^{2}}{|h_{i}|^{2}+|h_{i+G}|^{2}+\\epsilon},\\\\[10.0pt]\n901\tR_{j}^{(\\rho_{B})}=\\sum_{i\\in\\mathcal{C}_{j}}r_{i},\\\\\n902\t\\eta_{j}^{(\\rho_{B})}=10\\log_{10}\\frac{R_{j}^{(\\rho_{B})}}{\\operatorname{median}_{j}R_{j}^{(1)}}.\\end{gathered}\n903\t\n904\t(26)\n905\t\n906\tThis metric reflects the fact that a gauge-differential phase estimate becomes unstable when either\n907\tend of the gauge pair falls into a Rayleigh fading null. Accordingly, the metric characterizes the\n908\tfading-robustness mechanism of spatial joint processing.\n909\t\n910\tFigure 8: Bandwidth scaling at a fixed reporting interval in repeated No-CP OFDM DAS simulation. (a) Effective\n911\tdifferential-phase reliability distributions for 75–300 MHz after joint processing to a common\n912\treporting interval, normalized according to (26).\n913\t(b) Within-band reconstruction-SNR gain of spatial joint processing over a single fine-grid trace\n914\tversus ρB\\rho_{B}. Markers and error bars denote the event median and interquartile range; the dashed\n915\tline is the nominal 10​log10⁡(ρB)10\\log_{10}(\\rho_{B}) equal-reliability reference.\n916\t\n917\tFigure 8 evaluates this spatial-combining mechanism. In\n918\tFig. 8(a), increasing the occupied bandwidth from 75 MHz to\n919\t300 MHz shifts the reliability distribution to higher values while reducing the low-reliability\n920\ttail. This indicates that combining more fine spatial observations lowers the probability that a\n921\treported gauge-differential phase sample is dominated by a local Rayleigh fading null.\n922\tFigure 8(b) gives the within-band reconstruction-SNR gain\n923\tfrom spatial joint processing relative to a single fine-grid trace at the same occupied bandwidth.\n924\tThe median gain increases with ρB\\rho_{B} and follows the same trend as the nominal\n925\tequal-reliability averaging reference, although the wide interquartile ranges show that the gain is\n926\tscene- and fading-dependent. Deviations from the dashed line are consistent with nonuniform Rayleigh\n927\treliability and the weighted spatial combining used in the reconstruction. These results indicate\n928\tthat additional spatial samples can mitigate fading-induced weak points. Because the baseline in\n929\tFig. 8(b) is a single fine-grid trace at the\n930\tsame occupied bandwidth, the comparison isolates the spatial-combining gain from the bandwidth\n931\tchange. The result therefore characterizes spatial combining at a fixed reporting resolution under\n932\tthe modeled noise and fading conditions.\n933\t\n934\tThese numerical results are consistent with the design consequence in\n935\tSection II-C. Reducing the transmitted period from an explicit-CP frame\n936\tto the OFDM useful period increases the slow-time sampling rate for the same useful-block length\n937\tand fiber memory. In the present 5.2-km simulation configuration, the No-CP period gives a 9.16-kHz\n938\tslow-time Nyquist limit. The comparison therefore supports a period-limited sensing-bandwidth benefit,\n939\tand quantifies the effect of removing the explicitly transmitted CP from the probing period.\n940\t\n941\tIV Experimental Setup and Verification\n942\t\n943\tIV-A Experimental Setup\n944\t\n945\tThe experiment evaluates the repeated No-CP OFDM DAS waveform and tail-reuse receiver over a 5.2-km\n946\tfiber link. The optical architecture follows Fig. 1 and is similar to the\n947\theterodyne coherent platform used in the precursor CP-OFDM experiment [22],\n948\twith a continuously repeated No-CP OFDM useful block used as the probe.\n949\t\n950\tTABLE II: Experimental Parameters of the Repeated No-CP OFDM DAS System\n951\t\n952\tParameter\n953\t\n954\tValue\n955\t\n956\tLaser wavelength\n957\t\n958\t1550 nm\n959\t\n960\tLaser linewidth\n961\t\n962\t1 kHz\n963\t\n964\tAWG sampling rate\n965\t\n966\t512 MSa/s\n967\t\n968\tOscilloscope sampling rate\n969\t\n970\t1 GSa/s\n971\t\n972\tFiber length\n973\t\n974\t5.2 km\n975\t\n976\tBaseband processing rate\n977\t\n978\t128 MSa/s\n979\t\n980\tDigital IQ shift\n981\t\n982\t160 MHz\n983\t\n984\tOccupied OFDM bandwidth\n985\t\n986\t111.984 MHz\n987\t\n988\tActive/total subcarriers\n989\t\n990\t7167/8192\n991\t\n992\tSubcarrier spacing\n993\t\n994\t15.625 kHz\n995\t\n996\tEdge guard bandwidth per side\n997\t\n998\t8 MHz\n999\t\n1000\tOFDM size\n1001\t\n1002\t8192 samples\n1003\t\n1004\tCP length\n1005\t\n1006\t0 samples\n1007\t\n1008\tOFDM useful-block period\n1009\t\n1010\t64.0 μ\\mus\n1011\t\n1012\tNo-CP slow-time Nyquist limit\n1013\t\n1014\t7.81 kHz\n1015\t\n1016\tRF bandpass\n1017\t\n1018\t94–226 MHz\n1019\t\n1020\tNominal gauge length\n1021\t\n1022\t4 m\n1023\t\n1024\tRVS diversity channels\n1025\t\n1026\t33\n1027\t\n1028\tBlind search band\n1029\t\n1030\t300–7800 Hz\n1031\t\n1032\tA narrow-linewidth laser at 1550 nm provides the optical carrier. In the signal path, a Keysight\n1033\tM8190A arbitrary waveform generator (AWG) drives an ID Photonics OMFT-40 in-phase/quadrature (IQ)\n1034\tmodulator to generate the repeated No-CP OFDM probe. The probe is amplified by an erbium-doped fiber\n1035\tamplifier (EDFA) and launched into the sensing fiber with an input optical power of -11 dBm. The\n1036\tRayleigh backscatter returns through the circulator path, is detected by a 300-MHz balanced\n1037\tphotodetector (BPD), and is digitized by a RIGOL DHO4404 oscilloscope for offline processing. The\n1038\tnumerical waveform, link, and acquisition parameters are summarized in\n1039\tTable II.\n1040\t\n1041\tThe digital probe is generated on a 128-MSa/s complex-baseband grid with an 8192-sample useful OFDM\n1042\tblock. The repeated No-CP OFDM waveform does not activate all FFT bins. An 8-MHz guard band is reserved at\n1043\teach spectral edge, and the DC subcarrier is nulled. As a result, 7167 of the 8192 subcarriers are\n1044\tactive, giving an occupied OFDM bandwidth of 111.984 MHz. The experimental range response therefore\n1045\tfollows the band-limited kernel in (10). The baseband waveform\n1046\tis shifted to a 160-MHz intermediate frequency and exported to the AWG at 512 MSa/s. Each AWG\n1047\tsegment contains three identical useful periods and is looped continuously. The 64.0-μ\\mus useful\n1048\tperiod gives a 15.625-kHz slow-time sampling rate and a 7.81-kHz Nyquist limit.\n1049\t\n1050\tThe vibration is applied by a piezoelectric transducer (PZT) inserted after approximately 5.1 km of\n1051\tfiber and followed by an additional 100-m fiber segment. This\n1052\tlayout-defined position is treated as nominal because no independent absolute-distance calibration\n1053\twas performed. The following results use two representative 5-V sinusoidal PZT records, at 500 Hz\n1054\tand 3 kHz, acquired at the same perturbation position.\n1055\t\n1056\tFigure 9: Blind vibration localization in the 5.2-km repeated No-CP OFDM DAS experiment. Top: 500-Hz\n1057\tPZT record with a dominant spatially whitened score peak at 5063.7 m. Bottom: 3-kHz PZT record with\n1058\ta dominant peak at 5070.1 m.\n1059\t\n1060\tFigure 10: Experimental recovery of the 500-Hz PZT vibration. Upper composite: normalized recovered\n1061\tslow-time waveform at the detected range bin, data-derived tone fit, and vibration spectrum with a\n1062\tdominant peak at 499.7 Hz. Lower composite: full-record distance-time and frequency-time maps,\n1063\tshowing that the recovered response remains near the detected PZT region and near the 500-Hz drive\n1064\tover the acquisition interval.\n1065\t\n1066\tFigure 11: Experimental recovery of the 3-kHz PZT vibration. Upper composite: normalized recovered\n1067\tslow-time waveform at the detected range bin, data-derived tone fit, and vibration spectrum with a\n1068\tdominant component near the applied 3-kHz drive. Lower composite: full-record distance-time and\n1069\tfrequency-time maps, showing that the recovered response remains near the detected PZT region and\n1070\tnear 3 kHz over the acquisition interval.\n1071\t\n1072\tThe acquired oscilloscope waveform is processed offline using the DSP chain in\n1073\tFig. 3 and the exact repeated No-CP OFDM reference saved by the transmitter. The waveform is\n1074\tfirst mean-removed, normalized, filtered by a 94–226-MHz radio-frequency (RF) bandpass, digitally\n1075\tdownconverted at 160 MHz, and resampled to the 128-MSa/s OFDM processing grid. Because the received\n1076\twaveform contains neither an explicit CP nor a zero guard, the period boundary is not obtained from\n1077\ta CP correlation peak. Instead, candidate window starts are evaluated using the support-to-tail\n1078\tenergy criterion in (25). After frequency-domain deconvolution and inverse FFT\n1079\treconstruction, the selected boundary is the one that concentrates the reconstructed channel inside\n1080\tthe physical 0–5.2-km fiber support rather than in the circular FFT tail.\n1081\t\n1082\tThe selected one-period window is then processed by regularized active-subcarrier division and an\n1083\tinverse FFT. Rayleigh fading is mitigated by frequency-subband rotated-vector summation (RVS) using\n1084\t32 overlapping OFDM subbands together with the full-band estimate [22]. The\n1085\treconstructed channel is converted to gauge-differential phase with a 4-m nominal gauge length, and\n1086\tblind localization is performed from the spatially whitened slow-time spectrum over 300–7800 Hz.\n1087\t\n1088\tIV-B Experimental Verification\n1089\t\n1090\tThe driven fiber section is first localized without prior position or frequency information. For\n1091\teach valid gauge position, the recovered slow-time gauge-differential phase is transformed into the\n1092\tfrequency domain over the search band\n1093\tℬ=[300,7800]\\mathcal{B}=[300,7800] Hz. Let Pℓ​(f)P_{\\ell}(f) denote the resulting slow-time power spectrum at\n1094\trange bin ℓ\\ell. To suppress the range-dependent background and fading-induced contrast\n1095\tvariations, the spectrum is spatially whitened at each frequency as\n1096\t\n1097\tP~ℓ​(f)=Pℓ​(f)medianm∈𝒱​{Pm​(f)}+ϵ,\\widetilde{P}_{\\ell}(f)=\\frac{P_{\\ell}(f)}{\\mathrm{median}_{m\\in\\mathcal{V}}\\{P_{m}(f)\\}+\\epsilon},\n1098\t\n1099\t(27)\n1100\t\n1101\twhere 𝒱\\mathcal{V} is the set of valid range bins and ϵ\\epsilon is a small regularization term.\n1102\tThe blind localization score plotted in Fig. 9 is then defined as\n1103\t\n1104\tSℓdB=10​log10⁡maxf∈ℬ⁡P~ℓ​(f)maxm∈𝒱⁡maxf∈ℬ⁡P~m​(f).S_{\\ell}^{\\mathrm{dB}}=10\\log_{10}\\frac{\\max_{f\\in\\mathcal{B}}\\widetilde{P}_{\\ell}(f)}{\\max_{m\\in\\mathcal{V}}\\max_{f\\in\\mathcal{B}}\\widetilde{P}_{m}(f)}.\n1105\t\n1106\t(28)\n1107\t\n1108\tThe frequency-wise median provides a background reference across the valid fiber span, and the\n1109\tmaximization over ℬ\\mathcal{B} selects the strongest whitened narrowband response at each position.\n1110\tThe score is therefore obtained solely from the measured broadband response, without inserting the\n1111\tnominal PZT position or the applied drive tone. The same procedure is applied independently to the\n1112\t500-Hz and 3-kHz records.\n1113\t\n1114\tAs shown in Fig. 9, the 500-Hz record gives a dominant score peak\n1115\tat 5063.7 m, and the 3-kHz record gives a dominant score peak at 5070.1 m. The two independently\n1116\tobtained positions differ by 6.4 m and both fall near the nominal PZT region at the distal end of the\n1117\t5.2-km link. Because the PZT position is defined by the fiber layout without an independent\n1118\tabsolute-distance calibration, this separation serves as a measure of inter-record localization\n1119\tconsistency; no absolute localization error is assigned. The two distal responses therefore support\n1120\ta common physical origin within the driven fiber section.\n1121\t\n1122\tAfter the perturbation position is obtained, the slow-time gauge-differential phase is extracted at\n1123\tthe detected range bin for temporal, spectral, and full-record analysis. The two records are\n1124\tprocessed independently at their respective detected bins, with no further spatial search during\n1125\twaveform or time-frequency recovery. Each frequency case is therefore evaluated using the range\n1126\tlocation returned by its own blind localization result.\n1127\t\n1128\tFigure 11 presents the recovery result for the 500-Hz\n1129\trecord. At the detected range bin, the recovered trace follows the data-derived sinusoidal\n1130\tcomponent, and the spectrum has a distinct maximum at 499.7 Hz, 0.3 Hz from the nominal drive. The\n1131\tagreement in the time and frequency domains shows that the recovered phase evolution retains the\n1132\tapplied low-frequency oscillation. Over the full acquisition interval, the distance-time response\n1133\tremains near the localized distal region, while the frequency-time response remains concentrated\n1134\taround 500 Hz. These two maps extend the single-trace result to the complete record and show that the\n1135\trecovered component remains spatially localized and temporally persistent.\n1136\t\n1137\tFigure 11 provides the corresponding recovery evidence for the\n1138\t3-kHz record. The recovered waveform contains the expected denser oscillations, and its spectrum is\n1139\tconcentrated at 3002.1 Hz, within the 7.81-kHz slow-time Nyquist limit. The close agreement with the\n1140\tapplied drive confirms that the 3-kHz phase evolution is retained by the tail-reuse\n1141\treceiver. The full-record distance-time map remains concentrated near the nominal PZT region, and\n1142\tthe frequency-time map forms a persistent ridge near 3 kHz over successive slow-time windows.\n1143\t\n1144\tThe two records also impose distinct slow-time sampling demands. At the 15.625-kHz slow-time\n1145\tsampling rate, the 500-Hz and 3-kHz vibrations are represented by approximately 31 and 5 samples per\n1146\tcycle, respectively. The recovered peaks at 499.7 and 3002.1 Hz correspond to relative deviations\n1147\tof approximately 0.06% and 0.07% from the applied frequencies. The 3-kHz case therefore evaluates\n1148\tphase recovery with substantially fewer slow-time observations per vibration cycle while remaining\n1149\tbelow the 7.81-kHz Nyquist limit.\n1150\t\n1151\tTogether, the independently processed records show that the same tail-reuse receiver preserves\n1152\tblind localization, temporal phase evolution, and frequency recovery under different slow-time\n1153\tsampling demands. The persistent distance-time and frequency-time responses further confirm that\n1154\tthe recovered vibrations remain associated with the same physical fiber section throughout the\n1155\tacquisition interval.\n1156\t\n1157\tV Conclusion\n1158\t\n1159\tThis paper proposed and analyzed a repeated cyclic-prefix-free OFDM (No-CP OFDM) DAS waveform and\n1160\ttail-reuse receiver for coherent distributed vibration sensing. Under the valid range condition,\n1161\tthe receiver obtains the required cyclic extension from the preceding repeated useful-period tail\n1162\tinstead of transmitting a separate CP. The resulting useful-period FFT window supports\n1163\tfrequency-domain channel reconstruction and subsequent gauge-differential phase recovery. If the\n1164\tuseful period does not cover the physical channel memory, the reconstructed response becomes\n1165\tcircularly folded. The occupied bandwidth continues to determine the spatial resolution.\n1166\t\n1167\tRemoving the explicit CP shortens the slow-time probing period and raises the period-limited highest\n1168\tunaliased vibration frequency. In the 5.2-km numerical configuration, the 54.61-μ\\mus No-CP period\n1169\tgives a 9.16-kHz slow-time Nyquist limit, compared with 4.69 kHz for the sufficient-CP reference.\n1170\tSimulations verified tail-reuse reconstruction, the range-folding boundary, and dynamic recovery in\n1171\ta 100-event scene spanning 800 Hz to 8800 Hz. The No-CP receiver recovered the prescribed\n1172\tfrequencies across this range, whereas the continuous CP-OFDM reference produced aliased\n1173\tfrequencies above its lower Nyquist limit. This comparison demonstrates a period-limited\n1174\tsensing-bandwidth benefit from eliminating the explicitly transmitted CP. A secondary\n1175\tbandwidth-scaling simulation indicated that proportionally increasing the processing rate and\n1176\tuseful-block length can provide fine spatial observations for joint processing at a fixed reporting\n1177\tinterval under the modeled conditions.\n1178\t\n1179\tExperiments applied the same receiver chain to a 5.2-km coherent DAS link. In\n1180\tseparate measurements with 5-V PZT excitation at 500 Hz and 3 kHz, the receiver blindly localized\n1181\tthe driven fiber region at 5063.7 m and 5070.1 m, respectively. Both positions are close to the\n1182\tnominal PZT region near the distal end of the link. The recovered waveform and spectrum showed a\n1183\t499.7-Hz peak for the 500-Hz record and a dominant component near the applied 3-kHz drive. These\n1184\texperiments establish the feasibility of tail-reuse channel reconstruction and demonstrate\n1185\tlocalization, waveform recovery, frequency recovery, and localized time-frequency tracking at both\n1186\tdrive frequencies. The analytical model and the matched numerical comparison with continuous\n1187\tCP-OFDM support the corresponding extension of the period-limited unaliased vibration range.\n1188\t\n1189\tReferences\n1190\t\n1191\t[1]\n1192\t\n1193\tR. Posey, G. A. Johnson, and S. T. Vohra, “Strain sensing based on coherent\n1194\tRayleigh scattering in an optical fibre,” Electronics Letters,\n1195\tvol. 36, no. 20, pp. 1688–1689, 2000.\n1196\t\n1197\t[2]\n1198\t\n1199\tY. Lu, T. Zhu, L. Chen, and X. Bao, “Distributed vibration sensor based on\n1200\tcoherent detection of phase-OTDR,” Journal of Lightwave Technology,\n1201\tvol. 28, no. 22, pp. 3243–3249, 2010.\n1202\t\n1203\t[3]\n1204\t\n1205\tX. Bao and L. Chen, “Recent progress in distributed fiber optic sensors,”\n1206\tSensors, vol. 12, no. 7, pp. 8601–8639, 2012.\n1207\t\n1208\t[4]\n1209\t\n1210\tA. Masoudi and T. P. Newson, “Contributed review: Distributed optical fibre\n1211\tdynamic strain sensing,” Review of Scientific Instruments, vol. 87,\n1212\tno. 1, p. 011501, 2016.\n1213\t\n1214\t[5]\n1215\t\n1216\tY. Muanenda, “Recent advances in distributed acoustic sensing based on\n1217\tphase-sensitive optical time domain reflectometry,” Journal of\n1218\tSensors, vol. 2018, pp. 1–16, 2018.\n1219\t\n1220\t[6]\n1221\t\n1222\tJ. B. Ajo-Franklin, S. Dou, N. J. Lindsey, I. Monga, C. Tracy, M. Robertson,\n1223\tV. R. Tribaldos, C. Ulrich, B. Freifeld, T. Daley, and X. Li, “Distributed\n1224\tacoustic sensing using dark fiber for near-surface characterization and\n1225\tbroadband seismic event detection,” Scientific Reports, vol. 9, p.\n1226\t1328, 2019.\n1227\t\n1228\t[7]\n1229\t\n1230\tZ. He and Q. Liu, “Optical fiber distributed acoustic sensors: A review,”\n1231\tJournal of Lightwave Technology, vol. 39, no. 12, pp. 3671–3686,\n1232\t2021.\n1233\t\n1234\t[8]\n1235\t\n1236\tS. Yang, W. Zou, X. Long, and J. Chen, “Pulse-compression optical time domain\n1237\treflectometer,” in 23rd International Conference on Optical Fibre\n1238\tSensors, vol. 9157. SPIE, 2014, p.\n1239\t915736.\n1240\t\n1241\t[9]\n1242\t\n1243\tB. Lu, Z. Wang, H. Zheng, Q. Ye, R. Qu, H. Zhao, and H. Cai, “Pulse\n1244\tcompression phase sensitive optical time domain reflectometer with sub-meter\n1245\tresolution,” in 25th International Conference on Optical Fiber\n1246\tSensors, vol. 10323. SPIE, 2017, p.\n1247\t103230O.\n1248\t\n1249\t[10]\n1250\t\n1251\tM. Gonzalez-Herraez, A. Garcia-Ruiz, P. Corredera, J. Pastor-Graells, M. R.\n1252\tFernández-Ruiz, H. F. Martins, and S. Martin-Lopez, “Chirped-pulse\n1253\tphase-sensitive optical time-domain reflectometry,” in Asia\n1254\tCommunications and Photonics Conference 2016. OSA, 2016, p. AF1A.1.\n1255\t\n1256\t[11]\n1257\t\n1258\tJ. Pastor-Graells, H. F. Martins, A. Garcia-Ruiz, S. Martin-Lopez, and\n1259\tM. Gonzalez-Herraez, “Single-shot distributed temperature and strain\n1260\ttracking using direct detection phase-sensitive OTDR with chirped pulses,”\n1261\tOptics Express, vol. 24, no. 12, p. 13121, 2016.\n1262\t\n1263\t[12]\n1264\t\n1265\tM. R. Fernández-Ruiz, L. Costa, and H. F. Martins, “Distributed acoustic\n1266\tsensing using chirped-pulse phase-sensitive OTDR technology,”\n1267\tSensors, vol. 19, no. 20, p. 4368, 2019.\n1268\t\n1269\t[13]\n1270\t\n1271\tZ. Wang, B. Zhang, J. Xiong, Y. Fu, S. Lin, J. Jiang, Y. Chen, Y. Wu, Q. Meng,\n1272\tand Y. Rao, “Distributed acoustic sensing based on pulse-coding\n1273\tphase-sensitive OTDR,” IEEE Internet of Things Journal, vol. 6,\n1274\tno. 4, pp. 6117–6124, 2019.\n1275\t\n1276\t[14]\n1277\t\n1278\tP. Li, Y. Wang, P. Wang, Q. Bai, Y. Gao, H. Zhang, and B. Jin, “Pulse coding\n1279\tin distributed optical fiber vibration sensor: A review,” IEEE Sensors\n1280\tJournal, vol. 21, no. 20, pp. 22 371–22 387, 2021.\n1281\t\n1282\t[15]\n1283\t\n1284\tJ. Jiang, Z. Wang, Z. Wang, Z. Qiu, C. Liu, and Y. Rao, “Continuous\n1285\tchirped-wave phase-sensitive optical time domain reflectometry,”\n1286\tOptics Letters, vol. 46, no. 3, p. 685, 2021.\n1287\t\n1288\t[16]\n1289\t\n1290\tS. Weinstein and P. Ebert, “Data transmission by frequency-division\n1291\tmultiplexing using the discrete fourier transform,” IEEE Transactions\n1292\ton Communication Technology, vol. 19, no. 5, pp. 628–634, 1971.\n1293\t\n1294\t[17]\n1295\t\n1296\tL. Cimini, “Analysis and simulation of a digital mobile channel using\n1297\torthogonal frequency division multiplexing,” IEEE Transactions on\n1298\tCommunications, vol. 33, no. 7, pp. 665–675, 1985.\n1299\t\n1300\t[18]\n1301\t\n1302\tJ. A. C. Bingham, “Multicarrier modulation for data transmission: an idea\n1303\twhose time has come,” IEEE Communications Magazine, vol. 28, no. 5,\n1304\tpp. 5–14, 1990.\n1305\t\n1306\t[19]\n1307\t\n1308\tW. Shieh and C. Athaudage, “Coherent optical orthogonal frequency division\n1309\tmultiplexing,” Electronics Letters, vol. 42, no. 10, pp. 587–589,\n1310\t2006.\n1311\t\n1312\t[20]\n1313\t\n1314\tA. Lowery and J. Armstrong, “Orthogonal-frequency-division multiplexing for\n1315\tdispersion compensation of long-haul optical systems,” Optics\n1316\tExpress, vol. 14, no. 6, p. 2079, 2006.\n1317\t\n1318\t[21]\n1319\t\n1320\tJ. Armstrong, “OFDM for optical communications,” Journal of Lightwave\n1321\tTechnology, vol. 27, no. 3, pp. 189–204, 2009.\n1322\t\n1323\t[22]\n1324\t\n1325\tH. Huang, Z. Xue, Z. Chen, Z. Tian, D. Zou, G. Shen, and Y. Cai,\n1326\t“Cyclic-prefix OFDM probing for spatial-ISI-free distributed acoustic\n1327\tsensing via frequency-domain channel reconstruction,” arXiv:2606.19724\n1328\t[eess.SP], 2026. [Online]. Available: https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.19724\n1329\t\n1330\t[23]\n1331\t\n1332\tL. Marcon, A. Galtarossa, and L. Palmieri, “High-frequency high-resolution\n1333\tdistributed acoustic sensing by optical frequency domain reflectometry,”\n1334\tOptics Express, vol. 27, no. 10, p. 13923, 2019.\n1335\t\n1336\t \n1337\t\n1338\t Experimental support, please\n1339\t view the build logs\n1340\t for errors. Generated by\n1341\t \n1342\t \n1343\t L\n1344\t A\n1345\t T\n1346\t E\n1347\t \n1348\t xml\n1349\t \n1350\t .\n1351\t \n1352\t\n1353\t \n1354\t\n1355\t \n1356\tInstructions for reporting errors\n1357\t\n1358\t \n1359\tWe are continuing to improve HTML versions of papers, and your feedback helps enhance accessibility and mobile\n1360\t support. To report errors in the HTML that will help us improve conversion and rendering, choose any of the\n1361\t methods listed below:\n1362\t\n1363\t \n1364\t \n1365\tClick the \"Report Issue\" (\n1366\t \n1367\t ) button, located in the page header.\n1368\t \n1369\t \n1370\tTip: You can select the relevant text first, to include it in your report.\n1371\t\n1372\t \n1373\tOur team has already identified the following issues. We appreciate your time reviewing and reporting rendering errors we\n1374\t may not have found yet. Your efforts will help us improve the HTML versions for all readers, because disability\n1375\t should not be a barrier to accessing research. Thank you for your continued support in championing open access for\n1376\t all.\n1377\t\n1378\t \n1379\tHave a free development cycle? Help support accessibility at arXiv! Our collaborators at LaTeXML maintain a list of packages that need conversion, and welcome developer contributions.\n1380\t\n1381\t \n1382\t\n1383\t \n1384\t\n1385\t \n1386\t\n1387\t \n1388\t\n1389\t We gratefully acknowledge support from\n1390\t our major funders,\n1391\t member institutions, ,\n1392\t and all contributors.\n1393\t \n1394\t\n1395\t \n1396\t About\n1397\t ·\n1398\t Help\n1399\t ·\n1400\t Contact\n1401\t ·\n1402\t Subscribe\n1403\t ·\n1404\t Copyright\n1405\t ·\n1406\t Privacy\n1407\t ·\n1408\t Accessibility\n1409\t ·\n1410\t Operational Status (opens in new tab)\n1411\t \n1412\t \n1413\t\n1414\t \n1415\t\n1416\t \n1417\tMajor funding support from\n1418\t\n1419\t \n1420\t\n1421\t \n1422\t \n1423\t \n1424\t \n1425\t \n1426\t \n1427\t \n1428\t \n1429\t \n1430\t \n1431\t\n1432\t \n1433\t\n1434\t \n1435\t\n1436\t \n1437\t \n1438\t \n1439\t \n1440\t \n1441\t\n1442\t\n1443\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "04e7c3d7-ffac-4f34-8a9f-a2a6508ccc14", "uuid": "ce797c35-b42b-46d4-932b-2a6576aee77a", "timestamp": "2026-07-22T09:17:05.726Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/04e7c3d7-ffac-4f34-8a9f-a2a6508ccc14/tool-results/b7egfcqyp.txt", "content": "\n\nCyclic-Prefix-Free OFDM With Tail-Reuse Reconstruction for Distributed Acoustic Sensing\n\n \n \n Report GitHub Issue\n ×\n \n\n \n\n Title:\n \n\n \nContent selection saved. Describe the issue below:\n\n Description:\n \n \n\n \n Submit without GitHub\n Submit in GitHub\n \n \n\n \n arXiv is now an independent nonprofit!\n Learn more\n ×\n \n\n \n\n \n Back to arXiv\n \n \n\n \n \n Why HTML?\n \n \n \n \n Report Issue\n \n \n \n \n \n \n Back to Abstract\n \n \n \n \n \n \n Download PDF\n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n\nAbstract\n\nI Introduction\n\nII Principle and Signal Model\n\nII-A Finite-Memory DAS Channel and Effective Range Response\n\nII-B Repeated No-CP OFDM Tail-Reuse Reconstruction\n\nII-C Design Consequences: Overhead, Vibration Bandwidth, and Range\n\nII-D Validity Boundary and Practical Interpretation\n\nIII Numerical Simulation\n\nIII-A Simulation Configuration\n\nIII-B Tail-Reuse and Range-Condition Verification\n\nIII-C Dynamic Sensing and Slow-Time Bandwidth\n\nIII-D Bandwidth Scaling at a Fixed Reporting Interval\n\nIV Experimental Setup and Verification\n\nIV-A Experimental Setup\n\nIV-B Experimental Verification\n\nV Conclusion\n\nReferences\n\n \n License: arXiv.org perpetual non-exclusive license\n \n \n\narXiv:2607.18687v1 [eess.SP] 21 Jul 2026\n\nCyclic-Prefix-Free OFDM With Tail-Reuse Reconstruction for Distributed Acoustic Sensing\n\nZiang Chen, Zhiyang Xue, Zhongxing Tian, Zeyu Feng, Dongdong Zou,\n\nYi Cai*, Fellow, Optica and Huan Huang*, Member, IEEE\nManuscript received Month Day, Year; revised Month Day, Year. (Corresponding authors:\nYi Cai; Huan Huang.)The authors are with Soochow University, Suzhou, China (e-mail:\nyicai@suda.edu.cn; huanghuan@suda.edu.cn).\n\nAbstract\n\nOrthogonal frequency-division multiplexing (OFDM) enables frequency-domain reconstruction of the\ndistributed Rayleigh backscatter channel in coherent distributed acoustic sensing (DAS). However,\nan explicitly transmitted cyclic prefix (CP) lengthens the probing period and lowers the slow-time\nNyquist limit of each range cell. Here, we investigate a repeated cyclic-prefix-free OFDM (No-CP\nOFDM) waveform for DAS, using the preceding useful-period tail as a virtual cyclic extension. We\nderive the finite-memory range condition for tail-reuse reconstruction and identify circular folding\nwhen the useful period is shorter than the physical channel memory. Analysis shows that, for a fixed useful-block length\nand fiber memory, removing the explicit CP raises the period-limited highest unaliased vibration\nfrequency without altering the occupied-bandwidth-limited spatial resolution. For a 5.2-km numerical configuration, a 75-MSa/s\nprocessing rate and a 4096-sample useful block yield a 54.61-μ\\mus No-CP period and a 9.16-kHz\nslow-time Nyquist limit. Simulations verify tail reuse and the predicted range-folding boundary, and demonstrate recovery\nof 100 vibration events spanning 800 Hz to 8800 Hz. A bandwidth-scaling simulation further shows\nthat jointly processing fine spatial observations improves differential-phase reliability and\nreconstruction SNR at a fixed reporting interval under the modeled conditions. Experiments on a 5.2-km coherent DAS link with\n111.984-MHz occupied OFDM\nbandwidth blindly localize 500-Hz and 3-kHz piezoelectric transducer (PZT) vibrations at 5063.7 m\nand 5070.1 m, respectively. The corresponding waveforms and spectra are recovered from the detected\nrange bins. These experiments establish the feasibility of tail-reuse channel reconstruction and\nvibration recovery, while the period-limited extension of the unaliased vibration bandwidth is\nquantified analytically and verified numerically.\n\nIndex Terms: \nDistributed acoustic sensing, optical fiber sensing, cyclic-prefix-free OFDM, tail-reuse\nreconstruction, coherent detection.\n\nI Introduction\n\nDistributed acoustic sensing (DAS) based on coherent Rayleigh backscatter enables\noptical fiber to serve not only as a transmission medium but also as a distributed array of\nvibration-sensitive sensing points over large numbers of range bins. In a phase-sensitive optical\ntime-domain reflectometry (ϕ\\phi-OTDR) system, an optical probe\nis launched into the fiber, the weak Rayleigh backscatter is coherently detected, and dynamic strain\nor vibration is inferred from the slow-time evolution of the complex backscattered field at each\nrange position [1, 2]. Because the sensing element is the fiber\nitself, DAS can use deployed or purpose-installed cables to monitor long linear assets and extended\nphysical environments without placing individual electrical sensors along the path. This capability\nhas motivated distributed fiber-optic sensing for infrastructure, perimeter, geophysical, and\nseismic monitoring applications, including demonstrations using existing dark fiber for near-surface\ncharacterization and broadband event detection\n[3, 4, 5, 6, 7].\n\nThe usefulness of DAS is determined not only by whether a vibration can be detected, but also by\nhow sensing range, spatial resolution, signal-to-noise ratio (SNR), and vibration bandwidth are\nobtained simultaneously. These requirements are coupled. A longer fiber increases propagation\ndelay, attenuation, and the temporal memory of the backscatter channel; a finer spatial resolution\nrequires a shorter effective impulse response or larger waveform bandwidth; a higher SNR usually\nrequires more optical energy, processing gain, or coherent averaging; and a higher vibration\nfrequency requires faster slow-time sampling of each range cell. Therefore, a DAS waveform is not\nmerely an illumination signal. It also defines the range-domain point-spread function, the amount\nof useful energy per observation, the repetition period available for dynamic sampling, and the\nreceiver operation used to convert backscatter into a spatial trace. This coupling makes the\nprobing waveform and the reconstruction receiver central design choices in long-reach,\nhigh-bandwidth DAS.\n\nConventional short-pulse DAS offers a direct and intuitive range mapping: the pulse duration sets\nthe nominal spatial resolution, while the round-trip delay maps each backscatter sample to a fiber\nposition. This simplicity is one reason that pulse-based ϕ\\phi-OTDR remains a widely used\narchitecture for distributed vibration sensing. However, the same mechanism also produces a basic\nenergy–resolution tension. Increasing pulse width can inject more optical energy and improve SNR,\nbut it broadens the spatial response; shortening the pulse improves spatial resolution, but reduces\nthe available pulse energy unless the peak power is increased. In long-distance or high-bandwidth\nDAS, this tradeoff becomes more severe because the system must maintain enough backscattered SNR\nwhile preserving spatial selectivity and refreshing each range cell fast enough for dynamic\nmeasurements [3, 4].\n\nPulse-compression and coding techniques have been introduced to relax this tension by increasing\nthe time–bandwidth product or coding gain without simply broadening the final compressed response.\nEarly optical time-domain reflectometry studies used pulse-compression waveforms to improve the\nrange-resolved measurement process, and related ideas have been extended to phase-sensitive OTDR\nfor sub-meter-resolution vibration sensing\n[8, 9]. Chirped-pulse and swept-wave\napproaches further exploit frequency modulation to encode range-dependent phase or strain\ninformation, while coded-pulse schemes use structured sequences to improve sensitivity and reach\n[10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15].\nThese developments show that waveform design is an effective way to redistribute optical energy,\nbandwidth, and processing gain in DAS.\n\nDespite these advantages, many pulse-compression, chirped, and coded DAS receivers still recover\nthe range trace through linear correlation with a known replica of the transmitted waveform. The\nrecovered trace is therefore the fiber channel convolved with the aperiodic waveform\nautocorrelation. A narrow main lobe supports fine nominal spatial resolution, whereas sidelobes\nand finite main-lobe width spread the response of one fiber section into neighboring sections. In a\ndense Rayleigh backscatter channel, these off-peak correlation terms produce deterministic\ninter-range leakage that remains after coherent averaging. This motivates a receiver model that\ntreats the backscattered fiber as a finite-memory sensing channel and makes the effective range\nresponse explicit in the reconstruction process.\n\nFrequency-domain channel reconstruction provides a different viewpoint. In discrete\nFourier-transform OFDM, the transmitted block is synthesized from orthogonal subcarrier weights,\nand a cyclic prefix (CP) is inserted so that the useful block sees the finite-memory channel as a\ncircular convolution. After the discrete Fourier transform, the received sample on each active\nsubcarrier is proportional to the corresponding channel frequency response. This converts a\ntime-domain convolution problem into subcarrier-wise channel estimation or equalization, a principle\nthat has been central to multicarrier communication systems and later optical OFDM implementations\n[16, 17, 18, 19, 20, 21].\n\nWhen this principle is transferred from communications to DAS, the estimated channel takes on a\ndifferent role. In data transmission, the channel is an impairment to be equalized; in DAS, the\nrange-domain Rayleigh response is itself the sensing quantity. Our preceding CP-OFDM DAS study used\nknown OFDM subcarriers to estimate the active-bin channel response and reconstructed the range-domain\nchannel by inverse Fourier transform [22]. The effective range response is\ntherefore governed by subcarrier inversion and the active-frequency aperture rather than only by the\naperiodic probe autocorrelation. This reconstruction framework also exposes a DAS-specific cost: the\nCP lengthens each slow-time frame without providing an additional useful OFDM observation.\n\nIn DAS, the CP therefore imposes a sensing penalty. The OFDM block repetition period is the\nslow-time sampling interval of every recovered range cell. At a fixed sampling rate and useful-block\nlength, adding a CP lengthens each channel observation and lowers its slow-time Nyquist limit. Because\nthe prefix must cover the effective fiber memory, it can occupy a substantial fraction of the probing\nperiod over a long fiber. The same prefix that establishes circular convolution for frequency-domain\nreconstruction therefore reduces the vibration bandwidth available to each range cell.\n\nThis penalty is relevant to broadband, high-frequency, and high-spatial-resolution DAS\n[12, 23, 15, 7]. Optical\nfrequency-domain, swept/chirped, and pulse-coded approaches address these objectives through\ndifferent waveform and receiver tradeoffs. Within the OFDM channel-reconstruction framework,\nhowever, it remains unclear whether the required circular-convolution condition can be obtained\nwithout an explicitly transmitted CP. Resolving this issue would retain frequency-domain channel\nreconstruction while avoiding prefix samples that lower the highest unaliased vibration frequency.\n\nHere, we investigate repeated cyclic-prefix-free OFDM (No-CP OFDM) with tail-reuse reconstruction\nfor DAS. The known useful period is transmitted continuously so that the preceding-period tail\nprovides the virtual cyclic extension for the current period. The receiver then estimates the\nactive-bin channel response and reconstructs the range-domain channel without a separately\ntransmitted prefix. Tail\nreuse therefore retains the CP-OFDM channel-reconstruction interpretation while shortening the\nslow-time observation period.\n\nThe main contributions are as follows. First, we formulate a finite-memory model for repeated No-CP\nOFDM DAS and identify the condition under which the received useful block follows the circular-convolution\nrelation required for frequency-domain channel reconstruction. Second, we connect explicit-CP\noverhead to slow-time vibration bandwidth and range folding, thereby identifying when useful-period\nrepetition supplies the required cyclic extension. We also distinguish delay-grid sampling from\nbandwidth-limited spatial resolution. Third, simulations verify the predicted range boundary and\nhigh-frequency vibration recovery. They further evaluate the improvement in differential-phase\nreliability and reconstruction SNR obtained by jointly processing fine spatial observations enabled\nby bandwidth scaling at a fixed reporting interval. Finally, we implement a tail-reuse No-CP OFDM DAS\nreceiver and experimentally demonstrate blind localization and frequency recovery for 500-Hz and\n3-kHz vibrations over a 5.2-km fiber link.\n\nII Principle and Signal Model\n\nFig. 1 summarizes the coherent ϕ\\phi-OTDR DAS architecture considered in\nthis work. The section begins with a finite-memory sensing-channel model for a generic probing\nsequence and shows how correlation readout determines the effective range response. It then\nspecializes the probe to repeated No-CP OFDM and derives the tail-reuse circular-convolution\ncondition. The resulting design discussion connects the range-validity condition to CP overhead,\nslow-time vibration bandwidth, and unambiguous range, while distinguishing delay-grid sampling from\nbandwidth-limited spatial resolution.\n\nFigure 1: A coherent DAS system used for repeated cyclic-prefix-free OFDM (No-CP OFDM) probing.\nThe inset shows three repeated No-CP OFDM useful blocks without inserted CP samples. IQ: in-phase/quadrature;\nEDFA: erbium-doped fiber amplifier; OF: optical filter; OC: optical circulator;\nBPD: balanced photodiode; DSP: digital signal processing.\n\nII-A Finite-Memory DAS Channel and Effective Range Response\n\nThe starting point is the finite-memory sensing-channel view used in the CP-OFDM DAS precursor\n[22]. Over one slow-time frame pp, the coherent Rayleigh backscatter from the\nfiber is represented by the discrete range-domain channel\n𝐡p=[hp​[0],hp​[1],…,hp​[M−1]]T\\mathbf{h}_{p}=[h_{p}[0],h_{p}[1],\\ldots,h_{p}[M-1]]^{\\mathrm{T}}, where MM is the number of spatial cells\ncovered by the fiber under test. With sampling interval TsT_{s} and group velocity vgv_{g}, one discrete\ndelay bin corresponds to the two-way spatial increment Δ​z=vg​Ts/2\\Delta z=v_{g}T_{s}/2. For a transmitted\nbaseband probing sequence x​[n]x[n], the received sequence in frame pp is modeled as\n\nyp​[n]=∑m=0M−1hp​[m]​x​[n−m]+wp​[n],y_{p}[n]=\\sum_{m=0}^{M-1}h_{p}[m]x[n-m]+w_{p}[n],\n\n(1)\n\nwhere wp​[n]w_{p}[n] includes receiver noise and unmodeled impairments. The vibration-induced phase\nvariation is embedded in the slow-time evolution of hp​[m]h_{p}[m].\n\nThis model also clarifies the effective range response of conventional correlation-based DAS. If a\nfinite-duration probing waveform s​[n]s[n] is recovered through linear correlation with its known\nreplica, let rs​[ℓ]r_{s}[\\ell] denote its aperiodic autocorrelation, Es=rs​[0]E_{s}=r_{s}[0] its energy, and\ncs​[ℓ]=rs​[ℓ]/Esc_{s}[\\ell]=r_{s}[\\ell]/E_{s} its normalized autocorrelation response. The energy-normalized\nmatched-filter estimate at range bin ℓ\\ell can then be written as\n\nh^pMF​[ℓ]\\displaystyle\\hat{h}^{\\mathrm{MF}}_{p}[\\ell]\n\n=∑m=0M−1hp​[m]​cs​[ℓ−m]+ν~p​[ℓ]\\displaystyle=\\sum_{m=0}^{M-1}h_{p}[m]c_{s}[\\ell-m]+\\tilde{\\nu}_{p}[\\ell]\n\n(2)\n\n=hp​[ℓ]+∑m=0m≠ℓM−1hp​[m]​cs​[ℓ−m]+ν~p​[ℓ].\\displaystyle=h_{p}[\\ell]+\\sum_{\\begin{subarray}{c}m=0\\\\\nm\\neq\\ell\\end{subarray}}^{M-1}h_{p}[m]c_{s}[\\ell-m]+\\tilde{\\nu}_{p}[\\ell].\n\nThe summation term in (2) is the waveform-dependent leakage term: range bins\nother than ℓ\\ell enter the recovered bin through the off-peak samples of cs​[ℓ]c_{s}[\\ell]. A finer\nanalog-to-digital converter (ADC) grid may represent this point-spread function with more samples,\nbut it does not change the underlying autocorrelation-weighted response. The prior CP-OFDM\nframework instead forms a circular-convolution observation, estimates the loaded frequency bins,\nand transforms them back to the range domain [22]. Its effective range kernel\nis determined by the subcarrier inversion and active-frequency weighting. The present repeated\nNo-CP work keeps this reconstruction view but replaces the explicitly transmitted cyclic prefix\nwith useful-symbol repetition.\n\nII-B Repeated No-CP OFDM Tail-Reuse Reconstruction\n\nLet NN denote the OFDM useful-symbol length and let S​[k]S[k] be the known complex weight on the\nkkth subcarrier. One useful OFDM period is\n\ns​[n]=1N​∑k=0N−1S​[k]​ej​2​π​k​n/N,0≤n<N.s[n]=\\frac{1}{N}\\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}S[k]e^{j2\\pi kn/N},\\quad 0\\leq n<N.\n\n(3)\n\nIn the proposed repeated No-CP sensing waveform, no cyclic prefix, cyclic suffix, or zero guard is inserted.\nInstead, the same known useful OFDM period is transmitted continuously,\n\nx​[n]=s​[⟨n⟩N],x​[n+N]=x​[n],x[n]=s[\\langle n\\rangle_{N}],\\quad x[n+N]=x[n],\n\n(4)\n\nwhere ⟨n⟩N\\langle n\\rangle_{N} denotes the integer nn modulo NN.\n\nThe corresponding timing relation is illustrated in Fig. 2. Unlike\nconventional CP-OFDM, the highlighted tail is not a newly inserted guard interval; it is already part\nof the preceding useful OFDM period in the continuous transmitted stream. At the receiver, this tail\nis used as the virtual cyclic extension associated with the current useful period before channel\nreconstruction based on the fast Fourier transform (FFT) and frequency-domain equalization (FDE).\n\nFigure 2: Principle of virtual-CP construction in repeated No-CP OFDM with tail reuse. The\ntransmitted stream contains only repeated useful OFDM blocks. The tail of useful block n−1n-1 is reused at the receiver\nas the virtual CP for useful block nn, after which the useful block is processed by FFT/FDE. FFT: fast Fourier\ntransform; FDE: frequency-domain equalization.\n\nThe key observation formalized below is that a repeated useful period provides a virtual cyclic\nextension. For the current period, the last M−1M-1 samples of the previous period are identical to\nthe samples that would have been copied into an explicit cyclic prefix. Thus no additional prefix\nsamples are transmitted, but the linear fiber convolution can still be observed as a circular\nconvolution when the repeated period covers the channel memory. Under the range condition\n\nN≥M,N\\geq M,\n\n(5)\n\nand assuming that the channel is approximately constant over the previous-tail-plus-current-useful\nobservation interval, an aligned NN-sample receive window becomes\n\nup​[n]=∑m=0M−1hp​[m]​s​[⟨n−m⟩N]+wp​[n],0≤n<N.u_{p}[n]=\\sum_{m=0}^{M-1}h_{p}[m]s[\\langle n-m\\rangle_{N}]+w_{p}[n],\\quad 0\\leq n<N.\n\n(6)\n\nEquation (6) is the theoretical bridge from sufficient-CP OFDM to repeated\nNo-CP OFDM: the circular-convolution condition is preserved by repeating the known useful period,\nwhile the explicit CP is removed from the transmitted stream.\n\nTaking the NN-point discrete Fourier transform (DFT) of (6) gives\n\nUp​[k]\\displaystyle U_{p}[k]\n\n=S​[k]​Hp​[k]+Wp​[k],\\displaystyle=S[k]H_{p}[k]+W_{p}[k],\n\n(7)\n\nHp​[k]\\displaystyle H_{p}[k]\n\n=∑m=0M−1hp​[m]​e−j​2​π​k​m/N.\\displaystyle=\\sum_{m=0}^{M-1}h_{p}[m]e^{-j2\\pi km/N}.\n\nFor active subcarriers k∈𝒦k\\in\\mathcal{K}, the channel spectrum is estimated by one-tap\nregularized least squares (LS),\n\nH^p​[k]={Up​[k]​S∗​[k]|S​[k]|2+λ,k∈𝒦,0,k∉𝒦,\\hat{H}_{p}[k]=\\begin{cases}\\dfrac{U_{p}[k]S^{*}[k]}{|S[k]|^{2}+\\lambda},&k\\in\\mathcal{K},\\\\[5.69054pt]\n0,&k\\notin\\mathcal{K},\\end{cases}\n\n(8)\n\nwhere λ\\lambda controls noise enhancement near weak loaded subcarriers. The case λ=0\\lambda=0\ncorresponds to zero-forcing (ZF) inversion on the active set. The range-domain channel estimate is\nthen obtained by inverse DFT,\n\nh^p​[m]=1N​∑k=0N−1H^p​[k]​ej​2​π​k​m/N,0≤m<M.\\hat{h}_{p}[m]=\\frac{1}{N}\\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\\hat{H}_{p}[k]e^{j2\\pi km/N},\\quad 0\\leq m<M.\n\n(9)\n\nThe effective range response follows directly from\n(7)–(9). Define the deterministic frequency-domain\nweighting as Gλ​[k]G_{\\lambda}[k]. Then\n\nGλ​[k]\\displaystyle G_{\\lambda}[k]\n\n={|S​[k]|2|S​[k]|2+λ,k∈𝒦,0,k∉𝒦,\\displaystyle=\n\n(10)\n\ngλ​[m]\\displaystyle g_{\\lambda}[m]\n\n=1N​∑k=0N−1Gλ​[k]​ej​2​π​k​m/N,\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{N}\\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}G_{\\lambda}[k]e^{j2\\pi km/N},\n\nh^p​[m]\\displaystyle\\hat{h}_{p}[m]\n\n=∑q=0M−1hp​[q]​gλ​[⟨m−q⟩N]+w~p,λ​[m].\\displaystyle=\\sum_{q=0}^{M-1}h_{p}[q]g_{\\lambda}[\\langle m-q\\rangle_{N}]+\\tilde{w}_{p,\\lambda}[m].\n\nHere gλ​[m]g_{\\lambda}[m] is the circular point-spread function, and\nw~p,λ​[m]\\tilde{w}_{p,\\lambda}[m] is the correspondingly weighted noise. Equation (10)\nprovides a common description of full-bin reconstruction, inactive subcarriers, and regularization.\n\nProposition 1 (tail reuse for repeated No-CP reconstruction): Suppose that the same useful\nOFDM period is repeated, N≥MN\\geq M, the receiver window is aligned to a consistent periodic windowing\nphase, and the channel is quasi-static over the effective previous-tail-plus-current-useful\nobservation interval. In the ideal full-bin case with S​[k]≠0S[k]\\neq 0 for all kk and λ=0\\lambda=0, the\nZF reconstruction in (9) gives\n\nh^p​[m]=hp​[m]+w~p​[m],0≤m<M,\\hat{h}_{p}[m]=h_{p}[m]+\\tilde{w}_{p}[m],\\quad 0\\leq m<M,\n\n(11)\n\nwhere w~p​[m]\\tilde{w}_{p}[m] represents receiver noise after frequency-domain inversion and IDFT. If the noise term is absent,\nh^p​[m]=hp​[m]\\hat{h}_{p}[m]=h_{p}[m] on the DFT delay grid, and no deterministic contribution from q≠mq\\neq m range\nbins remains.\n\nTo see this, we substitute the definition of Hp​[k]H_{p}[k] in (7) into\n(9) with λ=0\\lambda=0 and full nonzero subcarrier loading, and obtain\n\nh^p​[m]=∑q=0M−1hp​[q]​[1N​∑k=0N−1ej​2​π​k​(m−q)/N]+w~p​[m].\\hat{h}_{p}[m]=\\sum_{q=0}^{M-1}h_{p}[q]\\left[\\frac{1}{N}\\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}e^{j2\\pi k(m-q)/N}\\right]+\\tilde{w}_{p}[m].\n\n(12)\n\nThe bracketed sum evaluates to δN​[m−q]\\delta_{N}[m-q], the Kronecker delta on an NN-periodic delay grid.\nOn the physical fiber support, the condition N≥MN\\geq M prevents modular wraparound between two\ndifferent range bins, so δN​[m−q]\\delta_{N}[m-q] acts as an ordinary Kronecker delta. The first term in\n(12) is therefore hp​[m]h_{p}[m]. The key distinction from explicit-CP OFDM is not\nthe frequency-domain estimator itself, but the origin of the cyclic extension. Here it is supplied\nby tail reuse of the preceding repeated period rather than by newly transmitted prefix samples. For\nconstant-modulus full-bin loading, the zero-regularization estimator in\n(8) is, up to a constant scale, mathematically equivalent to circular matched\nfiltering. Exact discrete-channel recovery then follows because the cyclic autocorrelation is a\nKronecker delta. With inactive bins or regularization, the effective response is instead\ngλ​[m]g_{\\lambda}[m] in (10).\n\nThe DAS vibration readout is obtained from the reconstructed channel through gauge-differential\nphase processing. For a gauge separation of GG samples, the complex gauge product and its phase\nchange relative to a reference frame p=0p=0 are\n\ng^p​[m]\\displaystyle\\hat{g}_{p}[m]\n\n=h^p​[m+G]​h^p∗​[m],0≤m<M−G,\\displaystyle=\\hat{h}_{p}[m+G]\\hat{h}_{p}^{*}[m],\\quad 0\\leq m<M-G,\n\n(13)\n\nΔ​ϕp​[m]\\displaystyle\\Delta\\phi_{p}[m]\n\n=∠​{g^p​[m]​g^0∗​[m]}.\\displaystyle=\\angle\\left\\{\\hat{g}_{p}[m]\\hat{g}_{0}^{*}[m]\\right\\}.\n\nThis operation converts slow-time changes in the reconstructed Rayleigh channel into local vibration\ntraces along the fiber.\n\nII-C Design Consequences: Overhead, Vibration Bandwidth, and Range\n\nThe repeated No-CP model links cyclic-extension overhead, slow-time sampling, and range validity in\nDAS operation. For a conventional CP-OFDM sensing waveform using the same useful-symbol length NN,\na sufficient CP must cover the finite channel memory,\n\nLCP≥M−1.L_{\\mathrm{CP}}\\geq M-1.\n\n(14)\n\nThe corresponding CP-OFDM and No-CP repetition periods are\n\nTCP=(N+LCP)​Ts,TNoCP=N​Ts.T_{\\mathrm{CP}}=(N+L_{\\mathrm{CP}})T_{s},\\quad T_{\\mathrm{NoCP}}=NT_{s}.\n\n(15)\n\nThus the useful-symbol-normalized CP overhead is LCP/NL_{\\mathrm{CP}}/N, and the fraction of a\nsufficient-CP frame occupied by CP samples is LCP/(N+LCP)L_{\\mathrm{CP}}/(N+L_{\\mathrm{CP}}). The No-CP\nwaveform does not remove the physical requirement that the channel memory be covered; instead, it\nreuses the previous repeated useful-period tail as the virtual cyclic extension.\n\nThe second consequence is an increase in the slow-time sampling rate relative to an explicit-CP\nimplementation with the same NN and fiber memory. Since DAS vibration recovery samples the channel\nonce per repeated probing period, the highest unaliased vibration frequency is bounded by\n\nfmax=12​Trep.f_{\\max}=\\frac{1}{2T_{\\mathrm{rep}}}.\n\n(16)\n\nTherefore,\n\nfmaxNoCPfmaxCP=TCPTNoCP=1+LCPN.\\frac{f_{\\max}^{\\mathrm{NoCP}}}{f_{\\max}^{\\mathrm{CP}}}=\\frac{T_{\\mathrm{CP}}}{T_{\\mathrm{NoCP}}}=1+\\frac{L_{\\mathrm{CP}}}{N}.\n\n(17)\n\nThe range-validity condition further links fiber length to slow-time bandwidth. Because\nTNoCP=N​TsT_{\\mathrm{NoCP}}=NT_{s} and N≥MN\\geq M,\n\nTNoCP≥M​Ts≈2​Lvg,fmaxNoCP≲vg4​L,T_{\\mathrm{NoCP}}\\geq MT_{s}\\approx\\frac{2L}{v_{g}},\\quad f_{\\max}^{\\mathrm{NoCP}}\\lesssim\\frac{v_{g}}{4L},\n\n(18)\n\nwhere LL is the fiber length. The round-trip propagation time therefore sets a lower bound on the\nvalid useful-period duration and an upper bound on the unaliased vibration frequency. By eliminating\na separately transmitted prefix, tail reuse allows repeated No-CP OFDM to approach this\nlength-constrained limit. Nevertheless, the useful period must still span the full fiber round-trip\nmemory to avoid range folding.\n\nFor a minimum-sufficient explicit-CP reference, substituting\nLCP≥M−1L_{\\mathrm{CP}}\\geq M-1 into (17) gives the\nperiod penalty needed to accommodate the same fiber memory. For completeness, if a CP-OFDM sensing\nimplementation additionally inserts a guard or idle interval of LgL_{\\mathrm{g}} samples between\nprobing blocks, its repetition period and the corresponding vibration-bandwidth ratio become\n\nTCP,rep=(N+LCP+Lg)​Ts,fmaxNoCPfmaxCP,rep=N+LCP+LgN.T_{\\mathrm{CP,rep}}=(N+L_{\\mathrm{CP}}+L_{\\mathrm{g}})T_{s},\\quad\\frac{f_{\\max}^{\\mathrm{NoCP}}}{f_{\\max}^{\\mathrm{CP,rep}}}=\\frac{N+L_{\\mathrm{CP}}+L_{\\mathrm{g}}}{N}.\n\n(19)\n\nEquation (19) generalizes the period comparison; the continuous CP-OFDM\nreference used in Section III corresponds to Lg=0L_{\\mathrm{g}}=0.\n\nThe same design variables also set the unambiguous circular-deconvolution range,\n\nΔ​z=vg​Ts2=vg2​Fs,Ramb=N​Δ​z.\\Delta z=\\frac{v_{g}T_{s}}{2}=\\frac{v_{g}}{2F_{s}},\\quad R_{\\mathrm{amb}}=N\\Delta z.\n\n(20)\n\nHere Δ​z\\Delta z is the DFT delay-grid sampling interval. The useful-block length must be\nchosen so that RambR_{\\mathrm{amb}} exceeds the physical fiber support; any excess unambiguous range is a\nrange-validity margin rather than a spatial-resolution gain. The physical resolving interval is instead\nset by the occupied frequency aperture,\n\nBocc=Nact​Δ​f,Δ​zres≈vg2​Bocc,B_{\\mathrm{occ}}=N_{\\mathrm{act}}\\Delta f,\\quad\\Delta z_{\\mathrm{res}}\\approx\\frac{v_{g}}{2B_{\\mathrm{occ}}},\n\n(21)\n\nwhere NactN_{\\mathrm{act}} is the number of active subcarriers and Δ​f\\Delta f is the subcarrier\nspacing. Thus the DFT delay-grid sampling interval, the unambiguous periodic range, and the\nbandwidth-limited resolving interval are related but distinct quantities.\n\nBandwidth expansion must be considered jointly with the processing rate and useful-block length. A\nwider probing band generally requires a higher complex-baseband processing rate Fs=1/TsF_{s}=1/T_{s}, and the\nresulting finer delay grid increases the discrete channel memory according to\n\nM≈2​L​Fsvg.M\\approx\\frac{2LF_{s}}{v_{g}}.\n\n(22)\n\nThe useful-block length must therefore increase with FsF_{s} to preserve\nN/Fs≥2​L/vgN/F_{s}\\geq 2L/v_{g}. Scaling NN and FsF_{s} proportionally leaves the useful-period duration,\nunambiguous sensing range, slow-time sampling rate, and vibration Nyquist limit unchanged. Because\nthe minimum valid useful-period duration is constrained by the fiber round-trip memory, this\nproportional scaling does not provide a further increase in the slow-time Nyquist limit. The\nadditional occupied bandwidth is instead expressed as a finer intrinsic spatial resolving interval.\n\nIf the output interval is deliberately held coarser than this intrinsic resolution, a reported\nspatial unit contains multiple resolvable fine-grid observations. Their nominal ratio is\n\nρB=BoccBtar,Btar≈vg2​Δ​ztar,\\rho_{B}=\\frac{B_{\\mathrm{occ}}}{B_{\\mathrm{tar}}},\\quad B_{\\mathrm{tar}}\\approx\\frac{v_{g}}{2\\Delta z_{\\mathrm{tar}}},\n\n(23)\n\nwhere Δ​ztar\\Delta z_{\\mathrm{tar}} is the target effective spatial resolution and BtarB_{\\mathrm{tar}}\nis the bandwidth required to support that resolution. Here, ρB\\rho_{B} characterizes the available\nspatial sampling ratio, not the number of statistically independent observations, because adjacent\ngauge-phase traces can remain correlated. Fine-grid traces with locally consistent slow-time\nresponses may be gain-aligned and combined within each reporting cell without temporal averaging,\nwhich can reduce sensitivity to individual Rayleigh fading nulls while preserving the frame rate.\nThe gain depends on power normalization, receiver noise bandwidth, fading statistics, and\ninter-trace correlation. This processing opportunity is not unique to repeated No-CP OFDM; tail reuse\nallows it to be retained without adding CP-induced slow-time overhead.\n\nII-D Validity Boundary and Practical Interpretation\n\nThe repeated No-CP principle requires the same known OFDM useful period to be transmitted\ncontinuously. If the useful period\nchanges from frame to frame, the previous period tail is no longer the cyclic continuation of the\ncurrent period and (6) no longer follows. The channel must also be\nquasi-static over the effective previous-tail-plus-useful observation interval.\n\nThe period-length condition in (5) defines the most important failure\nmode. If N<MN<M, the receiver cannot uniquely assign all physical ranges to one DFT delay grid. The\nperiodic deconvolution then recovers a folded channel,\n\nhp,fold​[r]=∑ℓ:r+ℓ​N<Mhp​[r+ℓ​N],0≤r<N,h_{p,\\mathrm{fold}}[r]=\\sum_{\\ell:\\,r+\\ell N<M}h_{p}[r+\\ell N],\\quad 0\\leq r<N,\n\n(24)\n\nso scatterers or perturbations separated by integer multiples of N​Δ​zN\\Delta z contribute to the same\nreconstructed bin. This folding is a range ambiguity of the periodic probing waveform, not a\nreceiver implementation artifact.\n\nEven when N≥MN\\geq M, the receiver must select a periodic windowing phase that maps the circularly\nreconstructed channel to the physical fiber span. When N>MN>M and the expected physical support is\nknown, a useful timing metric is the ratio between reconstructed energy inside that support and\nresidual energy in the circular tail,\n\nη​(q)=∑m=0M−1|h^p,q​[m]|2∑m=MN−1|h^p,q​[m]|2+ϵ,\\eta(q)=\\frac{\\sum_{m=0}^{M-1}|\\hat{h}_{p,q}[m]|^{2}}{\\sum_{m=M}^{N-1}|\\hat{h}_{p,q}[m]|^{2}+\\epsilon},\n\n(25)\n\nwhere qq denotes a candidate window start and ϵ\\epsilon prevents division by zero. Maximizing\nη​(q)\\eta(q) favors the alignment in which the reconstructed channel energy lies within the physical\nfiber span rather than wrapping into the unused DFT tail.\n\nWith edge guards, DC nulling, transmitter and receiver frequency responses, active-bin\nregularization, and finite SNR, the practical reconstruction is a band-limited and regularized\nchannel estimate. A grid-aligned point scatterer can be reconstructed as a Kronecker-delta response\non the DFT delay grid under Proposition 1, but an off-grid scatterer or a\nreduced active-frequency aperture produces a finite-bandwidth Dirichlet- or windowed-sinc-like\nresponse whose first-null scale is governed by 1/Bocc1/B_{\\mathrm{occ}}. The proposed repeated No-CP scheme\nuses periodic circular deconvolution to remove explicit CP overhead and increase the slow-time\nsampling rate under the stated range and timing conditions, while the spatial resolution remains\ngoverned by the occupied bandwidth.\n\nFigure 3: Transmitter and receiver DSP flow used in the repeated No-CP OFDM DAS simulation, from waveform\ngeneration to gauge-differential phase recovery. PRBS: pseudo-random binary sequence;\nQPSK: quadrature phase-shift keying; IFFT: inverse fast Fourier transform;\nFFT: fast Fourier transform; FDE: frequency-domain equalization.\n\nIII Numerical Simulation\n\nNumerical simulations first examine the signal-model predictions in Section II\nbefore the experimental test. They isolate the mechanism and boundary of the proposed repeated\nNo-CP tail-reuse reconstruction. The simulations first test the range\ncondition: whether the repeated useful OFDM period provides the virtual cyclic extension required\nfor channel reconstruction when N≥MN\\geq M, and how the reconstruction fails when this condition is\nviolated. Dynamic perturbation recovery then examines whether the same reconstruction chain can\nsupport DAS vibration readout under the modeled conditions. As a secondary design study, bandwidth\nscaling is examined at a fixed reporting interval.\n\nThe simulated transmitter and receiver digital signal processing (DSP) chain is summarized in\nFig. 3. The transmitter maps a known pseudo-random binary sequence to quadrature\nphase-shift keying (QPSK) symbols, generates the OFDM useful period, and repeats it without inserting\nexplicit CP samples. The receiver samples the backscattered signal, forms the virtual-CP observation\ndescribed in Section II-B, estimates the channel in the frequency domain,\ntransforms it back to range, and obtains the DAS phase map through gauge-differential processing.\n\nIII-A Simulation Configuration\n\nThe simulated link contains 5.2 km of sensing fiber, corresponding to an approximately\n52-μ\\mus round-trip channel memory. The reference OFDM bandwidth is set to 75 MHz, the\ncomplex-baseband sampling rate is 75 MSa/s, and the useful-block length is 4096 samples.\nThis combination gives a 54.61-μ\\mus useful period, a 5.46-km unambiguous reconstruction span,\nand a 1.333-m range-bin spacing. The corresponding channel memory is 3900 samples, so the useful\nperiod slightly exceeds the physical fiber support. The same known OFDM useful block is transmitted\nperiodically without an explicit CP, cyclic suffix, or zero guard, and the preceding-period tail\nprovides the virtual prefix used by the receiver.\n\nUnless otherwise stated, the tail-reuse, range-condition, and dynamic simulations use this 75-MHz\nconfiguration. The bandwidth-scaling study in\nSection III-D instead varies the occupied bandwidth while\nscaling the useful-block length proportionally.\n\nThe fiber backscatter is represented by a dense complex Rayleigh channel whose slow-time phase is\nlocally perturbed by prescribed vibration events. The channel is held constant within each OFDM\nperiod and updated at the slow-time sampling instants. Additive receiver noise is included before\nfrequency-domain channel estimation. After FFT-domain deconvolution and inverse FFT reconstruction,\nthe recovered range-domain channel is converted into vibration traces through gauge-differential\nphase processing. Table I summarizes the parameters used for the\ntail-reuse, range-condition, and dynamic simulations.\n\nThe nominal and shortened-period configurations test the valid and folded range conditions,\nrespectively. In the nominal case, N=4096>M=3900N=4096>M=3900; the shortened-period case retains the same\nreconstruction chain while deliberately violating this condition.\n\nThe continuous CP-OFDM reference used in the dynamic simulations transmits explicit-CP OFDM blocks\nback to back. It uses the same 4096-sample useful block, prepends a 3899-sample CP, and removes the\nCP before FFT-domain channel estimation. The otherwise matched reconstruction conditions isolate\nthe change in slow-time probing period introduced by the explicit CP.\n\nTABLE I: Parameters for the Tail-Reuse and Dynamic DAS Simulations\n\nParameter\n\nValue or setting\n\nFiber length\n\n5.2 km\n\nReference OFDM bandwidth\n\n75 MHz\n\nSampling rate\n\n75 MSa/s\n\nRange-bin spacing\n\n1.333 m\n\nEffective channel memory\n\n3900 samples\n\nGauge length\n\n2.667 m\n\nOFDM useful length\n\n4096 samples\n\nUnambiguous reconstruction range\n\n5.46 km\n\nNo-CP explicit CP length\n\n0 samples\n\nVirtual prefix length\n\n3899 samples\n\nNo-CP useful-period duration\n\n54.61 μ\\mus\n\nNo-CP slow-time frames\n\n150\n\nNo-CP Nyquist limit\n\n9.16 kHz\n\nReceiver SNR\n\n45 dB\n\nCP-OFDM explicit CP length\n\n3899 samples\n\nCP-OFDM block period\n\n106.60 μ\\mus\n\nCP-OFDM frames\n\n77 over the same 8.137-ms window\n\nCP-OFDM Nyquist limit\n\n4.69 kHz\n\nIII-B Tail-Reuse and Range-Condition Verification\n\nThe first simulation directly tests the range condition behind the virtual-CP reconstruction.\nSeven perturbation events are placed along the\n5.2-km fiber so that the reconstruction must assign responses over nearly the entire sensing span.\nThe event positions are 0.65, 1.65, 2.20, 2.60, 3.00, 3.85, and 5.00 km, and\nthe corresponding vibration frequencies are 500, 650, 800, 950, 1100, 1250, and\n1400 Hz, with the same 1-rad phase-modulation amplitude. The plotted traces in\nFig. 4 are single-block spatial snapshots selected from the\n109th repeated OFDM block, i.e., the 109th slow-time frame of a 150-frame simulation sequence.\nIn the valid configuration, N=4096N=4096 and M=3900M=3900, so the useful OFDM period is long enough to cover\nthe effective fiber memory. The tail of the preceding useful period can therefore supply the cyclic\nextension required by the current receive window, and the expected outcome is a spatial response\nlocalized at the physical event positions.\n\nFigure 4: Numerical comparison of valid repeated No-CP tail-reuse reconstruction and invalid N<MN<M\nrange folding. (a) When the useful period covers the fiber memory, events E1–E7 remain localized\nover the 5.2-km span. (b) With a 3.2-km unambiguous range, the response from the 3.2–5.2-km fiber\nsection folds into the reconstructed 0–2.0-km interval, while output beyond 3.2 km has no unique\nphysical-range interpretation. Both panels show the spatial differential-phase snapshot of the\n109th repeated OFDM block.\n\nFigure 4(a) follows this prediction. The labeled events\nE1–E7 are recovered at their prescribed distances, while the inter-event regions remain close to\nthe background level. This behavior is the numerical counterpart of\n(6): after virtual-CP construction, the receiver observes an effective\ncircular convolution over the physical fiber support and can reconstruct the range-domain channel by\nFFT-domain deconvolution and inverse FFT processing.\n\nThe same figure also shows the failure mode when the condition N≥MN\\geq M is deliberately violated.\nIn this invalid case, a short-period branch with Nfold<MN_{\\mathrm{fold}}<M is used, giving a 3.2-km\nmaximum unambiguous range that is smaller than the 5.2-km fiber length. As predicted by\n(24), the complex channel response from the physical 3.2–5.2-km section folds\ninto the reconstructed 0–2.0-km interval. Gauge-differential phase is calculated after this\ncomplex-channel superposition, so the resulting cross terms distort the phase response within the\npreceding range interval instead of producing simply shifted event replicas. Output beyond 3.2 km\nlies outside the valid reconstruction range and therefore has no unique physical-range interpretation.\n\nFigure 5: Distance–frequency detection map for the 100-event repeated No-CP OFDM DAS simulation.\nThe score combines median-normalized slow-time spectral magnitude with square-root-weighted spatial\nroot-mean-square phase activity. White circles mark the prescribed event coordinates from 50 m to\n5150 m and from 800 Hz to 8800 Hz.\n\nIII-C Dynamic Sensing and Slow-Time Bandwidth\n\nAfter the range condition has been tested, the same reconstruction chain is applied to dynamic\nperturbation scenes. A 100-event scene is used here to check whether the tail-reuse receiver can\nrecover a dense set of simultaneous vibration responses over the full sensing span. The vibration\npositions are uniformly distributed from 50 m to 5150 m, and the vibration frequencies are\nuniformly swept from 800 Hz to 8800 Hz. All events have the same 0.5-rad phase-modulation\namplitude with random initial phases. The tail-reuse No-CP reconstruction uses 150 slow-time frames\nand gives an 8.137-ms monitoring window. This frequency range remains below the 9.16-kHz No-CP slow-time\nNyquist limit. For comparison, the continuous CP-OFDM reference follows the schedule defined in\nSection III-A. It provides 77 slow-time samples over the same\nmonitoring window, with a 106.60-μ\\mus block period and a 4.69-kHz Nyquist limit.\n\nFigure 5 presents the reconstructed scene in the\ndistance–frequency plane. At each distance cell, the slow-time spectral magnitude is normalized by\nits non-DC median and weighted by the square root of the normalized spatial root-mean-square phase\nactivity. The resulting score is normalized to its global maximum for visualization. The bright\nnarrowband responses follow the 100 prescribed distance–frequency coordinates across the full\n5.2-km span. Their alignment with the preset markers shows that the tail-reuse receiver preserves\nthe joint range and frequency assignment of the simulated events, consistent with the valid range\ncondition in Fig. 4.\n\nThe joint distance–frequency result in Fig. 5 is then\nexamined in the slow-time domain through representative traces.\nFigure 6 compares\nfour events selected from the same 100-event simulation. For the events near 0.8 kHz and 3.5 kHz,\nboth the No-CP tail-reuse receiver and the continuous CP-OFDM reference remain below the CP-OFDM\nNyquist limit, so the displayed waveforms are close. For the events near 6.1 kHz and 8.8 kHz,\nhowever, the continuous CP-OFDM slow-time sampling rate is below the requirement and the displayed\nwaveforms appear at the corresponding aliased frequencies. The No-CP traces continue to follow the\nhigh-frequency oscillations because the useful-block repetition period provides the larger\nslow-time sampling rate.\n\nFigure 6: Recovered vibration waveforms for representative events in the 100-event simulation.\nThe No-CP tail-reuse result is compared with the continuous CP-OFDM reference over a 2-ms\nslow-time window. The panel titles list the event position, prescribed vibration frequency, and\ncontinuous CP-OFDM alias frequency.\n\nThe same trend is summarized in the frequency domain in Fig. 7.\nThe recovered dominant frequency is plotted against\nthe prescribed vibration frequency for 50 representative events selected from the 100-event scene.\nThe No-CP tail-reuse result follows the ideal no-alias relation across the 800-Hz to 8800-Hz\nfrequency span. By contrast, the continuous CP-OFDM result follows the ideal line only below its\n4.69-kHz Nyquist limit and then folds to lower recovered frequencies. This frequency-domain view is\nconsistent with the waveform examples in Fig. 6 and shows\nthat the high-frequency recovery is a consequence of the larger slow-time sampling rate provided by\nthe repeated useful OFDM period.\n\nFigure 7: Recovered vibration frequency versus prescribed vibration frequency for 50 representative\nevents selected from the 100-event simulation. The dotted vertical line marks the continuous\nCP-OFDM Nyquist limit.\n\nIII-D Bandwidth Scaling at a Fixed Reporting Interval\n\nFor this design study, the occupied bandwidth is increased from 75 MHz to 150, 225, and 300 MHz,\nwith the receiver processing rate increased correspondingly from 75 MSa/s to 150, 225, and\n300 MSa/s. The useful-block length is scaled proportionally from 4096 samples to 8192, 12288, and\n16384 samples. The useful-period\nduration, unambiguous sensing range, slow-time sampling rate, and final reporting interval therefore\nremain fixed, while the reconstructed range response is sampled on progressively finer spatial\ngrids. Locally consistent fine-grid gauge-phase observations are then combined within each reporting\ncell without temporal averaging.\n\nFor the reliability distribution in Fig. 8(a), an\neffective differential-phase reliability is used as a mechanism-level diagnostic. Let hih_{i} and\nhi+Gh_{i+G} denote two complex Rayleigh channel samples separated by the gauge spacing GG. The\nsingle fine-sample reliability, the joint reliability of reporting cell 𝒞j\\mathcal{C}_{j}, and the\nnormalized dB quantity plotted in Fig. 8(a) are defined as\n\nri=|hi|2​|hi+G|2|hi|2+|hi+G|2+ϵ,Rj(ρB)=∑i∈𝒞jri,ηj(ρB)=10​log10⁡Rj(ρB)medianj⁡Rj(1).\\begin{gathered}r_{i}=\\frac{|h_{i}|^{2}|h_{i+G}|^{2}}{|h_{i}|^{2}+|h_{i+G}|^{2}+\\epsilon},\\\\[10.0pt]\nR_{j}^{(\\rho_{B})}=\\sum_{i\\in\\mathcal{C}_{j}}r_{i},\\\\\n\\eta_{j}^{(\\rho_{B})}=10\\log_{10}\\frac{R_{j}^{(\\rho_{B})}}{\\operatorname{median}_{j}R_{j}^{(1)}}.\\end{gathered}\n\n(26)\n\nThis metric reflects the fact that a gauge-differential phase estimate becomes unstable when either\nend of the gauge pair falls into a Rayleigh fading null. Accordingly, the metric characterizes the\nfading-robustness mechanism of spatial joint processing.\n\nFigure 8: Bandwidth scaling at a fixed reporting interval in repeated No-CP OFDM DAS simulation. (a) Effective\ndifferential-phase reliability distributions for 75–300 MHz after joint processing to a common\nreporting interval, normalized according to (26).\n(b) Within-band reconstruction-SNR gain of spatial joint processing over a single fine-grid trace\nversus ρB\\rho_{B}. Markers and error bars denote the event median and interquartile range; the dashed\nline is the nominal 10​log10⁡(ρB)10\\log_{10}(\\rho_{B}) equal-reliability reference.\n\nFigure 8 evaluates this spatial-combining mechanism. In\nFig. 8(a), increasing the occupied bandwidth from 75 MHz to\n300 MHz shifts the reliability distribution to higher values while reducing the low-reliability\ntail. This indicates that combining more fine spatial observations lowers the probability that a\nreported gauge-differential phase sample is dominated by a local Rayleigh fading null.\nFigure 8(b) gives the within-band reconstruction-SNR gain\nfrom spatial joint processing relative to a single fine-grid trace at the same occupied bandwidth.\nThe median gain increases with ρB\\rho_{B} and follows the same trend as the nominal\nequal-reliability averaging reference, although the wide interquartile ranges show that the gain is\nscene- and fading-dependent. Deviations from the dashed line are consistent with nonuniform Rayleigh\nreliability and the weighted spatial combining used in the reconstruction. These results indicate\nthat additional spatial samples can mitigate fading-induced weak points. Because the baseline in\nFig. 8(b) is a single fine-grid trace at the\nsame occupied bandwidth, the comparison isolates the spatial-combining gain from the bandwidth\nchange. The result therefore characterizes spatial combining at a fixed reporting resolution under\nthe modeled noise and fading conditions.\n\nThese numerical results are consistent with the design consequence in\nSection II-C. Reducing the transmitted period from an explicit-CP frame\nto the OFDM useful period increases the slow-time sampling rate for the same useful-block length\nand fiber memory. In the present 5.2-km simulation configuration, the No-CP period gives a 9.16-kHz\nslow-time Nyquist limit. The comparison therefore supports a period-limited sensing-bandwidth benefit,\nand quantifies the effect of removing the explicitly transmitted CP from the probing period.\n\nIV Experimental Setup and Verification\n\nIV-A Experimental Setup\n\nThe experiment evaluates the repeated No-CP OFDM DAS waveform and tail-reuse receiver over a 5.2-km\nfiber link. The optical architecture follows Fig. 1 and is similar to the\nheterodyne coherent platform used in the precursor CP-OFDM experiment [22],\nwith a continuously repeated No-CP OFDM useful block used as the probe.\n\nTABLE II: Experimental Parameters of the Repeated No-CP OFDM DAS System\n\nParameter\n\nValue\n\nLaser wavelength\n\n1550 nm\n\nLaser linewidth\n\n1 kHz\n\nAWG sampling rate\n\n512 MSa/s\n\nOscilloscope sampling rate\n\n1 GSa/s\n\nFiber length\n\n5.2 km\n\nBaseband processing rate\n\n128 MSa/s\n\nDigital IQ shift\n\n160 MHz\n\nOccupied OFDM bandwidth\n\n111.984 MHz\n\nActive/total subcarriers\n\n7167/8192\n\nSubcarrier spacing\n\n15.625 kHz\n\nEdge guard bandwidth per side\n\n8 MHz\n\nOFDM size\n\n8192 samples\n\nCP length\n\n0 samples\n\nOFDM useful-block period\n\n64.0 μ\\mus\n\nNo-CP slow-time Nyquist limit\n\n7.81 kHz\n\nRF bandpass\n\n94–226 MHz\n\nNominal gauge length\n\n4 m\n\nRVS diversity channels\n\n33\n\nBlind search band\n\n300–7800 Hz\n\nA narrow-linewidth laser at 1550 nm provides the optical carrier. In the signal path, a Keysight\nM8190A arbitrary waveform generator (AWG) drives an ID Photonics OMFT-40 in-phase/quadrature (IQ)\nmodulator to generate the repeated No-CP OFDM probe. The probe is amplified by an erbium-doped fiber\namplifier (EDFA) and launched into the sensing fiber with an input optical power of -11 dBm. The\nRayleigh backscatter returns through the circulator path, is detected by a 300-MHz balanced\nphotodetector (BPD), and is digitized by a RIGOL DHO4404 oscilloscope for offline processing. The\nnumerical waveform, link, and acquisition parameters are summarized in\nTable II.\n\nThe digital probe is generated on a 128-MSa/s complex-baseband grid with an 8192-sample useful OFDM\nblock. The repeated No-CP OFDM waveform does not activate all FFT bins. An 8-MHz guard band is reserved at\neach spectral edge, and the DC subcarrier is nulled. As a result, 7167 of the 8192 subcarriers are\nactive, giving an occupied OFDM bandwidth of 111.984 MHz. The experimental range response therefore\nfollows the band-limited kernel in (10). The baseband waveform\nis shifted to a 160-MHz intermediate frequency and exported to the AWG at 512 MSa/s. Each AWG\nsegment contains three identical useful periods and is looped continuously. The 64.0-μ\\mus useful\nperiod gives a 15.625-kHz slow-time sampling rate and a 7.81-kHz Nyquist limit.\n\nThe vibration is applied by a piezoelectric transducer (PZT) inserted after approximately 5.1 km of\nfiber and followed by an additional 100-m fiber segment. This\nlayout-defined position is treated as nominal because no independent absolute-distance calibration\nwas performed. The following results use two representative 5-V sinusoidal PZT records, at 500 Hz\nand 3 kHz, acquired at the same perturbation position.\n\nFigure 9: Blind vibration localization in the 5.2-km repeated No-CP OFDM DAS experiment. Top: 500-Hz\nPZT record with a dominant spatially whitened score peak at 5063.7 m. Bottom: 3-kHz PZT record with\na dominant peak at 5070.1 m.\n\nFigure 10: Experimental recovery of the 500-Hz PZT vibration. Upper composite: normalized recovered\nslow-time waveform at the detected range bin, data-derived tone fit, and vibration spectrum with a\ndominant peak at 499.7 Hz. Lower composite: full-record distance-time and frequency-time maps,\nshowing that the recovered response remains near the detected PZT region and near the 500-Hz drive\nover the acquisition interval.\n\nFigure 11: Experimental recovery of the 3-kHz PZT vibration. Upper composite: normalized recovered\nslow-time waveform at the detected range bin, data-derived tone fit, and vibration spectrum with a\ndominant component near the applied 3-kHz drive. Lower composite: full-record distance-time and\nfrequency-time maps, showing that the recovered response remains near the detected PZT region and\nnear 3 kHz over the acquisition interval.\n\nThe acquired oscilloscope waveform is processed offline using the DSP chain in\nFig. 3 and the exact repeated No-CP OFDM reference saved by the transmitter. The waveform is\nfirst mean-removed, normalized, filtered by a 94–226-MHz radio-frequency (RF) bandpass, digitally\ndownconverted at 160 MHz, and resampled to the 128-MSa/s OFDM processing grid. Because the received\nwaveform contains neither an explicit CP nor a zero guard, the period boundary is not obtained from\na CP correlation peak. Instead, candidate window starts are evaluated using the support-to-tail\nenergy criterion in (25). After frequency-domain deconvolution and inverse FFT\nreconstruction, the selected boundary is the one that concentrates the reconstructed channel inside\nthe physical 0–5.2-km fiber support rather than in the circular FFT tail.\n\nThe selected one-period window is then processed by regularized active-subcarrier division and an\ninverse FFT. Rayleigh fading is mitigated by frequency-subband rotated-vector summation (RVS) using\n32 overlapping OFDM subbands together with the full-band estimate [22]. The\nreconstructed channel is converted to gauge-differential phase with a 4-m nominal gauge length, and\nblind localization is performed from the spatially whitened slow-time spectrum over 300–7800 Hz.\n\nIV-B Experimental Verification\n\nThe driven fiber section is first localized without prior position or frequency information. For\neach valid gauge position, the recovered slow-time gauge-differential phase is transformed into the\nfrequency domain over the search band\nℬ=[300,7800]\\mathcal{B}=[300,7800] Hz. Let Pℓ​(f)P_{\\ell}(f) denote the resulting slow-time power spectrum at\nrange bin ℓ\\ell. To suppress the range-dependent background and fading-induced contrast\nvariations, the spectrum is spatially whitened at each frequency as\n\nP~ℓ​(f)=Pℓ​(f)medianm∈𝒱​{Pm​(f)}+ϵ,\\widetilde{P}_{\\ell}(f)=\\frac{P_{\\ell}(f)}{\\mathrm{median}_{m\\in\\mathcal{V}}\\{P_{m}(f)\\}+\\epsilon},\n\n(27)\n\nwhere 𝒱\\mathcal{V} is the set of valid range bins and ϵ\\epsilon is a small regularization term.\nThe blind localization score plotted in Fig. 9 is then defined as\n\nSℓdB=10​log10⁡maxf∈ℬ⁡P~ℓ​(f)maxm∈𝒱⁡maxf∈ℬ⁡P~m​(f).S_{\\ell}^{\\mathrm{dB}}=10\\log_{10}\\frac{\\max_{f\\in\\mathcal{B}}\\widetilde{P}_{\\ell}(f)}{\\max_{m\\in\\mathcal{V}}\\max_{f\\in\\mathcal{B}}\\widetilde{P}_{m}(f)}.\n\n(28)\n\nThe frequency-wise median provides a background reference across the valid fiber span, and the\nmaximization over ℬ\\mathcal{B} selects the strongest whitened narrowband response at each position.\nThe score is therefore obtained solely from the measured broadband response, without inserting the\nnominal PZT position or the applied drive tone. The same procedure is applied independently to the\n500-Hz and 3-kHz records.\n\nAs shown in Fig. 9, the 500-Hz record gives a dominant score peak\nat 5063.7 m, and the 3-kHz record gives a dominant score peak at 5070.1 m. The two independently\nobtained positions differ by 6.4 m and both fall near the nominal PZT region at the distal end of the\n5.2-km link. Because the PZT position is defined by the fiber layout without an independent\nabsolute-distance calibration, this separation serves as a measure of inter-record localization\nconsistency; no absolute localization error is assigned. The two distal responses therefore support\na common physical origin within the driven fiber section.\n\nAfter the perturbation position is obtained, the slow-time gauge-differential phase is extracted at\nthe detected range bin for temporal, spectral, and full-record analysis. The two records are\nprocessed independently at their respective detected bins, with no further spatial search during\nwaveform or time-frequency recovery. Each frequency case is therefore evaluated using the range\nlocation returned by its own blind localization result.\n\nFigure 11 presents the recovery result for the 500-Hz\nrecord. At the detected range bin, the recovered trace follows the data-derived sinusoidal\ncomponent, and the spectrum has a distinct maximum at 499.7 Hz, 0.3 Hz from the nominal drive. The\nagreement in the time and frequency domains shows that the recovered phase evolution retains the\napplied low-frequency oscillation. Over the full acquisition interval, the distance-time response\nremains near the localized distal region, while the frequency-time response remains concentrated\naround 500 Hz. These two maps extend the single-trace result to the complete record and show that the\nrecovered component remains spatially localized and temporally persistent.\n\nFigure 11 provides the corresponding recovery evidence for the\n3-kHz record. The recovered waveform contains the expected denser oscillations, and its spectrum is\nconcentrated at 3002.1 Hz, within the 7.81-kHz slow-time Nyquist limit. The close agreement with the\napplied drive confirms that the 3-kHz phase evolution is retained by the tail-reuse\nreceiver. The full-record distance-time map remains concentrated near the nominal PZT region, and\nthe frequency-time map forms a persistent ridge near 3 kHz over successive slow-time windows.\n\nThe two records also impose distinct slow-time sampling demands. At the 15.625-kHz slow-time\nsampling rate, the 500-Hz and 3-kHz vibrations are represented by approximately 31 and 5 samples per\ncycle, respectively. The recovered peaks at 499.7 and 3002.1 Hz correspond to relative deviations\nof approximately 0.06% and 0.07% from the applied frequencies. The 3-kHz case therefore evaluates\nphase recovery with substantially fewer slow-time observations per vibration cycle while remaining\nbelow the 7.81-kHz Nyquist limit.\n\nTogether, the independently processed records show that the same tail-reuse receiver preserves\nblind localization, temporal phase evolution, and frequency recovery under different slow-time\nsampling demands. The persistent distance-time and frequency-time responses further confirm that\nthe recovered vibrations remain associated with the same physical fiber section throughout the\nacquisition interval.\n\nV Conclusion\n\nThis paper proposed and analyzed a repeated cyclic-prefix-free OFDM (No-CP OFDM) DAS waveform and\ntail-reuse receiver for coherent distributed vibration sensing. Under the valid range condition,\nthe receiver obtains the required cyclic extension from the preceding repeated useful-period tail\ninstead of transmitting a separate CP. The resulting useful-period FFT window supports\nfrequency-domain channel reconstruction and subsequent gauge-differential phase recovery. If the\nuseful period does not cover the physical channel memory, the reconstructed response becomes\ncircularly folded. The occupied bandwidth continues to determine the spatial resolution.\n\nRemoving the explicit CP shortens the slow-time probing period and raises the period-limited highest\nunaliased vibration frequency. In the 5.2-km numerical configuration, the 54.61-μ\\mus No-CP period\ngives a 9.16-kHz slow-time Nyquist limit, compared with 4.69 kHz for the sufficient-CP reference.\nSimulations verified tail-reuse reconstruction, the range-folding boundary, and dynamic recovery in\na 100-event scene spanning 800 Hz to 8800 Hz. The No-CP receiver recovered the prescribed\nfrequencies across this range, whereas the continuous CP-OFDM reference produced aliased\nfrequencies above its lower Nyquist limit. This comparison demonstrates a period-limited\nsensing-bandwidth benefit from eliminating the explicitly transmitted CP. A secondary\nbandwidth-scaling simulation indicated that proportionally increasing the processing rate and\nuseful-block length can provide fine spatial observations for joint processing at a fixed reporting\ninterval under the modeled conditions.\n\nExperiments applied the same receiver chain to a 5.2-km coherent DAS link. In\nseparate measurements with 5-V PZT excitation at 500 Hz and 3 kHz, the receiver blindly localized\nthe driven fiber region at 5063.7 m and 5070.1 m, respectively. Both positions are close to the\nnominal PZT region near the distal end of the link. The recovered waveform and spectrum showed a\n499.7-Hz peak for the 500-Hz record and a dominant component near the applied 3-kHz drive. These\nexperiments establish the feasibility of tail-reuse channel reconstruction and demonstrate\nlocalization, waveform recovery, frequency recovery, and localized time-frequency tracking at both\ndrive frequencies. The analytical model and the matched numerical comparison with continuous\nCP-OFDM support the corresponding extension of the period-limited unaliased vibration range.\n\nReferences\n\n[1]\n\nR. Posey, G. A. Johnson, and S. T. Vohra, “Strain sensing based on coherent\nRayleigh scattering in an optical fibre,” Electronics Letters,\nvol. 36, no. 20, pp. 1688–1689, 2000.\n\n[2]\n\nY. Lu, T. Zhu, L. Chen, and X. Bao, “Distributed vibration sensor based on\ncoherent detection of phase-OTDR,” Journal of Lightwave Technology,\nvol. 28, no. 22, pp. 3243–3249, 2010.\n\n[3]\n\nX. Bao and L. Chen, “Recent progress in distributed fiber optic sensors,”\nSensors, vol. 12, no. 7, pp. 8601–8639, 2012.\n\n[4]\n\nA. Masoudi and T. P. Newson, “Contributed review: Distributed optical fibre\ndynamic strain sensing,” Review of Scientific Instruments, vol. 87,\nno. 1, p. 011501, 2016.\n\n[5]\n\nY. Muanenda, “Recent advances in distributed acoustic sensing based on\nphase-sensitive optical time domain reflectometry,” Journal of\nSensors, vol. 2018, pp. 1–16, 2018.\n\n[6]\n\nJ. B. Ajo-Franklin, S. Dou, N. J. Lindsey, I. Monga, C. Tracy, M. Robertson,\nV. R. Tribaldos, C. Ulrich, B. Freifeld, T. Daley, and X. Li, “Distributed\nacoustic sensing using dark fiber for near-surface characterization and\nbroadband seismic event detection,” Scientific Reports, vol. 9, p.\n1328, 2019.\n\n[7]\n\nZ. He and Q. Liu, “Optical fiber distributed acoustic sensors: A review,”\nJournal of Lightwave Technology, vol. 39, no. 12, pp. 3671–3686,\n2021.\n\n[8]\n\nS. Yang, W. Zou, X. Long, and J. Chen, “Pulse-compression optical time domain\nreflectometer,” in 23rd International Conference on Optical Fibre\nSensors, vol. 9157. SPIE, 2014, p.\n915736.\n\n[9]\n\nB. Lu, Z. Wang, H. Zheng, Q. Ye, R. Qu, H. Zhao, and H. Cai, “Pulse\ncompression phase sensitive optical time domain reflectometer with sub-meter\nresolution,” in 25th International Conference on Optical Fiber\nSensors, vol. 10323. SPIE, 2017, p.\n103230O.\n\n[10]\n\nM. Gonzalez-Herraez, A. Garcia-Ruiz, P. Corredera, J. Pastor-Graells, M. R.\nFernández-Ruiz, H. F. Martins, and S. Martin-Lopez, “Chirped-pulse\nphase-sensitive optical time-domain reflectometry,” in Asia\nCommunications and Photonics Conference 2016. OSA, 2016, p. AF1A.1.\n\n[11]\n\nJ. Pastor-Graells, H. F. Martins, A. Garcia-Ruiz, S. Martin-Lopez, and\nM. Gonzalez-Herraez, “Single-shot distributed temperature and strain\ntracking using direct detection phase-sensitive OTDR with chirped pulses,”\nOptics Express, vol. 24, no. 12, p. 13121, 2016.\n\n[12]\n\nM. R. Fernández-Ruiz, L. Costa, and H. F. Martins, “Distributed acoustic\nsensing using chirped-pulse phase-sensitive OTDR technology,”\nSensors, vol. 19, no. 20, p. 4368, 2019.\n\n[13]\n\nZ. Wang, B. Zhang, J. Xiong, Y. Fu, S. Lin, J. Jiang, Y. Chen, Y. Wu, Q. Meng,\nand Y. Rao, “Distributed acoustic sensing based on pulse-coding\nphase-sensitive OTDR,” IEEE Internet of Things Journal, vol. 6,\nno. 4, pp. 6117–6124, 2019.\n\n[14]\n\nP. Li, Y. Wang, P. Wang, Q. Bai, Y. Gao, H. Zhang, and B. Jin, “Pulse coding\nin distributed optical fiber vibration sensor: A review,” IEEE Sensors\nJournal, vol. 21, no. 20, pp. 22 371–22 387, 2021.\n\n[15]\n\nJ. Jiang, Z. Wang, Z. Wang, Z. Qiu, C. Liu, and Y. Rao, “Continuous\nchirped-wave phase-sensitive optical time domain reflectometry,”\nOptics Letters, vol. 46, no. 3, p. 685, 2021.\n\n[16]\n\nS. Weinstein and P. Ebert, “Data transmission by frequency-division\nmultiplexing using the discrete fourier transform,” IEEE Transactions\non Communication Technology, vol. 19, no. 5, pp. 628–634, 1971.\n\n[17]\n\nL. Cimini, “Analysis and simulation of a digital mobile channel using\northogonal frequency division multiplexing,” IEEE Transactions on\nCommunications, vol. 33, no. 7, pp. 665–675, 1985.\n\n[18]\n\nJ. A. C. Bingham, “Multicarrier modulation for data transmission: an idea\nwhose time has come,” IEEE Communications Magazine, vol. 28, no. 5,\npp. 5–14, 1990.\n\n[19]\n\nW. Shieh and C. Athaudage, “Coherent optical orthogonal frequency division\nmultiplexing,” Electronics Letters, vol. 42, no. 10, pp. 587–589,\n2006.\n\n[20]\n\nA. Lowery and J. Armstrong, “Orthogonal-frequency-division multiplexing for\ndispersion compensation of long-haul optical systems,” Optics\nExpress, vol. 14, no. 6, p. 2079, 2006.\n\n[21]\n\nJ. Armstrong, “OFDM for optical communications,” Journal of Lightwave\nTechnology, vol. 27, no. 3, pp. 189–204, 2009.\n\n[22]\n\nH. Huang, Z. Xue, Z. Chen, Z. Tian, D. Zou, G. Shen, and Y. Cai,\n“Cyclic-prefix OFDM probing for spatial-ISI-free distributed acoustic\nsensing via frequency-domain channel reconstruction,” arXiv:2606.19724\n[eess.SP], 2026. [Online]. Available: https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.19724\n\n[23]\n\nL. Marcon, A. Galtarossa, and L. Palmieri, “High-frequency high-resolution\ndistributed acoustic sensing by optical frequency domain reflectometry,”\nOptics Express, vol. 27, no. 10, p. 13923, 2019.\n\n \n\n Experimental support, please\n view the build logs\n for errors. Generated by\n \n \n L\n A\n T\n E\n \n xml\n \n .\n \n\n \n\n \nInstructions for reporting errors\n\n \nWe are continuing to improve HTML versions of papers, and your feedback helps enhance accessibility and mobile\n support. To report errors in the HTML that will help us improve conversion and rendering, choose any of the\n methods listed below:\n\n \n \nClick the \"Report Issue\" (\n \n ) button, located in the page header.\n \n \nTip: You can select the relevant text first, to include it in your report.\n\n \nOur team has already identified the following issues. We appreciate your time reviewing and reporting rendering errors we\n may not have found yet. Your efforts will help us improve the HTML versions for all readers, because disability\n should not be a barrier to accessing research. Thank you for your continued support in championing open access for\n all.\n\n \nHave a free development cycle? Help support accessibility at arXiv! Our collaborators at LaTeXML maintain a list of packages that need conversion, and welcome developer contributions.\n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n We gratefully acknowledge support from\n our major funders,\n member institutions, ,\n and all contributors.\n \n\n \n About\n ·\n Help\n ·\n Contact\n ·\n Subscribe\n ·\n Copyright\n ·\n Privacy\n ·\n Accessibility\n ·\n Operational Status (opens in new tab)\n \n \n\n \n\n \nMajor funding support from\n\n \n\n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n \n \n \n \n\n\n", "numLines": 1443, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 1443}}}
